{ "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f8f8b3d831d6a003afe" }, "answer" : "{Sigurd} [accept {Sigfried} or {Sivard Snarensvend}; prompt on “the {noble hart}”]", "category" : "Mythology", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 97.79976018494926, "num" : 1, "question" : "This figure, depicted in the Ramsund Carving, acquired his horse at the river Busiltjorn. Heimar hid this man's daughter in a harp; that daughter, Aslaug, later married Ragnar Lodbrok. He kills and is killed by a son of Gjuki named Guttorm. Tasting the blood of one of his enemies allowed him to understand the language of birds, one of whom informed him that his foster father Regin would betray him. This owner of Grani took the form of Gunnar to leap through a ring of fire and win Brynhild, though he himself married Gudrun. His father gave him the sword Gram, which he used to kill Fafnir. For 10 points, identify this hero of the Volsung Saga, the son of Sigmund.", "round" : "USF + Editors 6 - T Party 2010.doc", "seen" : 65, "tournament" : "T-Party", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3e988b3d831d6a00013a" }, "answer" : "{total internal} reflection [accept {Goos-Hanchen effect} before mention; accept {TIR} ; prompt on partial answers]", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "Open", "fixed" : 1, "inc_random" : 50.02025454351678, "num" : 5, "question" : "A quantum analogue of this effect was discovered to cause different time delays resulting in slightly different positions after passing a potential well in spinor neutrons by de Haan, et al in 2010. When polarized light undergoes this effect, light shifts perpendicular to the direction of propagation and the occurrence of this effect results in imaginary values in the coefficients derived from Fresnel’s formulas. Near field standing waves that form after undergoing this effect decay exponentially as they are not allowed to transport energy. Those waves are called evanescent waves, which can be coupled in the frustrated form of this effect that is analogous to quantum tunneling. The value above, which this effect will occur is given by the arcsine of the ratio of the indices of refraction of the media between which light undergoing this effect is passing. The operational principle behind optical fibers, for 10 points, name this effect that occurs when light strikes a boundary past the critical angle that causes complete reflection.", "round" : "2011-ACFNationals-MichiganAFinal.doc", "seen" : 32, "tournament" : "ACF Nationals", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e40378b3d831d6a006268" }, "answer" : "sutras", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 46.41451378515922, "num" : 2, "question" : "Alopen wrote a series of these texts with titles like Cause, Effect, and Salvation that are collectively known as the “Lost” ones of Jesus.  One of these texts claims that even four lines of it incorporated into one's sabhana will lead to blessing, and takes the form of a dialogue between Subhuti and another person.  Another of these texts tells a story about a man who convinces his children to leave a burning house by bribing them with toys, illustrating upaya, or “expedient means,” and claims that the Bodhisattva must strive for Buddhic wisdom.  For 10 points, identify these religious texts, such as the Mahayana Diamond and Lotus ones, as well as the Kama one, a love manual.", "round" : "ACF Fall 2008 - Brown.doc", "seen" : 30, "tournament" : "ACF Fall", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2008 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ed28b3d831d6a000e42" }, "answer" : "Prince {William} Arthur Philip Louis of Wales", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : 1, "inc_random" : 343.5085865831934, "num" : 21, "question" : "This man participated in his first rescue mission as co-pilot of the Sea King in October 2010. This man proposed to his fiancé during a trip to the Lewa reserve in Kenya. Due to marry Kate Middleton in April 2011, for 10 points, name this eldest son of Prince Charles, second in line to the throne of United Kingdom.", "round" : "regionals-08.pdf", "seen" : 235, "tournament" : "HSAPQ VHSL Regionals", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3edc8b3d831d6a0010b0" }, "answer" : "stomach", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 394.5191018213518, "num" : 18, "question" : "In full-grown humans, ghrelin is produced in larger quantities in this region than in the pancreas. It's not the brain, but APUD cells in this organ produce large amounts of serotonin, and one end of this organ is bounded by the pyloric sphincter. One disease that can afflict this organ is combated by increased release of prostaglandin, and is called gastritis, and this organ is aided in its primary function by the use of hydrochloric acid. For 10 points, name this organ, the first stop for food after being swallowed.", "round" : "25.pdf", "seen" : 263, "tournament" : "HSAPQ VHSL Regular Season", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f328b3d831d6a00247a" }, "answer" : "The {Charging Chasseur} of the {Imperial Guard} [also accept {Officer} of the {Imperial Guard}, or {Officier} de {chasseurs} à {cheval} de la {garde impériale chargeant}]", "category" : "Fine Arts", "difficulty" : "Open", "inc_random" : 35.81073695956729, "num" : 6, "question" : "On the far right of this work, there is a destroyed cannon's wheel. That side sees fire give rise to a wispy smoke dominating the background, which includes a cut-off figure looking out to the left. The central figure wears a green shirt, orange sash, white pants and black boots, and that figure has a surprisingly stoic look on his face. Its painter's first exhibited work, the central figures sports a (*) mustache and a curved sword in his right hand; he is also seated on a large leopard skin. In a twist of irony, its painter would eventually die after taking a nasty fall from a horse. For 10 points, identify this depiction of one of Napoleon's soldiers on a rearing horse, a painting by Theodore Gericault.", "round" : "Lully 1.doc", "seen" : 24, "tournament" : "Chicago Open Arts", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ef88b3d831d6a001735" }, "answer" : "{Second Paris Commune} [or {Communards}]", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 343.3801283235662, "num" : 8, "question" : "One memoir recounting this period was written by the author of “The Red Carnation,” poet and schoolteacher Louise Michel. Several people who appeared in a photograph with a fallen statue by the destroyed Vendôme column during this period were later tracked down; many others involved in this event were executed at the Wall of the Federalists, and thousands were imprisoned on the island of New Caledonia. It attempted to exchange several of its prisoners for Louis Auguste (*) Blanqui, and, after actions like seizure of cannons on the Butte of Montmartre and burning of Hotel de Ville, the “Bloody Week” led to its defeat by Adolphe Thiers’s opposition. For 10 points, name this 1871 Marxist uprising that briefly took over the capital of the newly formed French Third Republic.", "round" : "Packet 3 - Prelims 3.doc", "seen" : 230, "tournament" : "PACE NSC", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f2e8b3d831d6a002387" }, "answer" : "{Eusebius} of {Caesarea}", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "Open", "inc_random" : 42.42152264597826, "num" : 2, "question" : "The fourth book of one this historian's works closes by discussing Bardesanes and his dialogue On Fate, before noting how Soter died, while another part of that work discusses a period of misrule in which figures like the brothers Adesius and Apphianus both died at the hands of mobs. He was the manager of the Augustus's purple making factory while in Tyre, where he met Pamphilus, his collaborator with him on a defense of Origen. He sent the emperor a copy of his treatise on the Paschal Festival, which led to his stringent correspondence with Copnstantia. His most notable work contains an appendix on the martyrs of Palestine, and begins by stating how he is writing an account of the holy apostles. For 10 points, name this man that delivered the opening address to Constantine at the Council of Nicaea, a father of the church known for his church histories.", "round" : "2010 - Chicago Open - Round 06 - An Orderly Universe of Discoverable Laws.doc", "seen" : 26, "tournament" : "Chicago Open", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e40388b3d831d6a0062b5" }, "answer" : "{Colorado} River", "category" : "Geography", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 102.8660943566356, "num" : 16, "question" : "The Dolores and Virgin Rivers are tributaries of this larger river, and it flows by the Vermillion Cliffs National Monument. Fort Collins is located to the East of the Poudre Pas Lake, where this river begins. One can go gambling in the casino at Lake Havasu City which lies along this river, while Interstate Highway 10 crosses it near the city of Blythe. The Gila River is a tributary of this river which empties into the Gulf of California, while Lake Powell lies on it due to the creation of the Glen Canyon dam. For 10 points, identify this long river in the American Southwest which shares its name with a state and also passes through the Grand Canyon.", "round" : "ACF Fall 2008 - Dartmouth A.doc", "seen" : 69, "tournament" : "ACF Fall", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2008 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e40418b3d831d6a006495" }, "answer" : "Blindness [AR]", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "Open", "inc_random" : 31.87086154799908, "num" : 12, "question" : "In this work, some characters while crossing a square overhear speakers “extolling the virtues of the fundamental principles of the great organized systems, private property, a free currency market, [and] the stock exchange,” which leaves one of the main characters silent. Its sequel centers on a parliamentary election where the majority of people cast blank ballots, and in a late scene, the protagonists enter a church whose artwork is covered in bandages. One character in this novel stabs the leader of a group of hoodlums with a pair of scissors, and is consoled by a dog who licks away her tears. It opens at a traffic signal where a car does not respond to a green light, and its characters include “the doctor” and the “doctor's wife.” For 10 points, name this novel which recounts a social breakdown after an epidemic of the titular condition, written by Jose Saramago.", "round" : "Packet_8.doc", "seen" : 21, "tournament" : "Chicago Open Literature", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2008 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f908b3d831d6a003b2f" }, "answer" : "{Integrins} (prompt on {glycoproteins})", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 66.05009420868009, "num" : 8, "question" : "The RGD domain of von Willebrand factor binds to one of these proteins, and the anti-angiogenic factor cilengitide binds to one of these. The receptor for adenovirus is one of these molecules. Glanzmann's Thrombasthenia is caused by a defect in one of these proteins. The anticoagulant monoclonal antibody abciximab attacks one of these proteins, which binds to fibrinogen in an ADP-dependent manner. The N-termini of their alpha-subunits bind to divalent cations. The binding of talin binds to and activates these proteins, which can trigger the activity of focal adhesion kinases. These heavily glycosylated proteins consist of a heterodimer of an alpha and beta subunit, which bind to collagen and other extracellular matrix components. For 10 points, name these cell surface proteins named for the fact that they are integral to the cell membrane.", "round" : "THUNDER Finals 1.docx", "seen" : 46, "tournament" : "THUNDER II", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f5f8b3d831d6a002f19" }, "answer" : "{Harold Hart Crane}", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 46.2375164097175, "num" : 7, "question" : "One work by this writer asks \"Whose sweet mortality stirs latent power?\" and describes a \"bell-rope that gathers God at dawn.\" This poet of \"My Grandmother's Love Letters\" dubbed cinemas \"panoramic sleights\" in a poem that imagines filing papers until \"elevators drop us from our day\" and asks the title object to descend with its \"curveship\" and \"lend a myth to God.\" He imagines a seagull \"shedding white rings of tumult, building high / over the chained bay waters\" in the \"Proem\" to an epic based on a Brooklyn landmark. For 10 points, name this American poet who included sections like \"Cape Hatteras\" and \"Cutty Sark\" in his modernist epic The Bridge.", "round" : "MUT 2010 - EP Tony - Done.doc", "seen" : 29, "tournament" : "MUT", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3fb48b3d831d6a004368" }, "answer" : "{Sir Arthur Seymour Sullivan}", "category" : "Fine Arts", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 59.74167021038011, "num" : 3, "question" : "This artist composed an overture in the style of Mendelssohn for an opera which includes the songs “When Love and Beauty,” “Over the Roof,” and “Then come not yet.” In one of this composer's last operas, Ludwig replaces the miserly Grand Duke Rudolph of Pfennig Halbfennig; that opera is subtitled “The Statutory Duel.” This composer wrote the music for an opera in which The Gods of Mount Olympus go on a holiday, and an opera about a war between peers and fairies subtitled “The Peer and the Peri.” The composer of Cox and Box, The Grand Duke, Thespis, and Iolanthe, for 10 points, name this composer of the Savoy Theatre who collaborated on The Mikado and The HMS Pinafore with W. S. Gilbert.", "round" : "2009 ACF Regionals - CMU.doc", "seen" : 40, "tournament" : "ACF Regionals", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f7e8b3d831d6a0036ce" }, "answer" : "{John Hoyer Updike}", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 45.58015931537375, "num" : 5, "question" : "James Wood argued in his essay about this man's \"Complacent God\" that his writing was more style than content. He has written about a New Jersey teenager who attempted to bomb the Lincoln Tunnel, and published a poetry collection called \"Endpoint\" and essays called \"Due Considerations.\" In one story, he writes that Stokesie has \"two babies chalked up on his fuselage already,\" and the main character lusts after Queenie, an unknown girl in a bathing suit. Most of his novels are set in fictional Olinger, Pennsylvania and Eastwick, Rhode Island, and they including the Bech books, Buchanan stories, and \"The Scarlet Letter\" trilogy, while he is best known for a trilogy involving one character, whose first book ends with the pregnancy of his mistress after his legitimate daughter is accidentally drowned. For 10 points, name this American author of Terrorist and \"A&P\" best known for his character Harry \"Rabbit\" Angstrom.", "round" : "ColumbiaC.doc", "seen" : 29, "tournament" : "Princeton Buzzerfest", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3efb8b3d831d6a0017f8" }, "answer" : "{John Locke}", "category" : "Philosophy", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 466.5426088683307, "num" : 2, "question" : "This philosopher advises autodidacts on rational thinking in Of the Conduct of the Understanding, and emphasizes psychosomatic connections and explains how to teach virtue and reason in Some Thoughts Concerning Education. This thinker argues that more religious groups prevent civil unrest in A Letter Concerning Toleration, while in his most famous work he rejects the divine-right theory, arguing for a civil government based on universal rights and the social contract. A proponent of the theory of tabula rasa, for 10 points, name this philosopher who wrote Two Treatises of Government and An Essay Concerning Human Understanding.", "round" : "Round04.doc", "seen" : 308, "tournament" : "Prison Bowl", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3eff8b3d831d6a0018e1" }, "answer" : "{French} [or {Français}]", "category" : "Fine Arts", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 421.8044098201208, "num" : 7, "question" : "One opera written in this language is based on the Book of Judges, and features the mezzo-soprano aria \"Softly awakes my heart.\" In another opera written in this language, Nilakantha sings the \"Bell Song,\" and Mallika and the title character sing the \"Flower Duet.\" Most nineteenth century grand operas were written in this language. This language of the operas (*) Lakme and Samson and Delilah was also used for an opera featuring the Habanera and the Toreador Song. For 10 points, name this language used for Carmen by Georges Bizet.", "round" : "11.pdf", "seen" : 282, "tournament" : "HSAPQ Tournament 16", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ff08b3d831d6a00514b" }, "answer" : "Hannibal", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 344.6408594052773, "num" : 29, "question" : "This man was the victorious commander at a battle that saw the bribing of the grain outpost commander at Clastidium and in which his half-brother Mago opened with an ambush. In addition to defeating Tiberius Sempronius Longus at Trebia, this man ambushed Gaius Flaminius and drove Roman forces into Lake Trasimene. This man's brother's head was thrown into his camp at one point. This man was victorious at Cannae before losing at Zama. For 10 points, name this commander during the Second Punic War, the Carthaginian brother of Hasdrubal and son of Hamilcar Barca.", "round" : "4q2-06.pdf", "seen" : 229, "tournament" : "HSAPQ 4Q2", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ebf8b3d831d6a0009f8" }, "answer" : "The {Tin Drum}", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 45.78606871608645, "num" : 8, "question" : "One character in this novel is killed while trying to make love to the figurehead of a wooden ship. Another character in this work dies after seeing eels being pulled from a dead horse. In addition to Herbert Truczinski, another character in this novel becomes a lover of Roswitha Raguna after joining Bebra's group of performers. Jan Bronski steals a necklace for Agnes in this novel. Its protagonist can shatter glass with his voice and refuses to grow any more at the age of three. It is followed by Cat and Mouse and Dog Years in its author's Danzig Trilogy. For 10 points, name this novel about Oskar Matzerath, who cherishes the title instrument, written by Gunter Grass.", "round" : "Lisle and Maryland B.doc", "seen" : 32, "tournament" : "ACF Fall", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e40818b3d831d6a0073d1" }, "answer" : "{Crimean} War", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 343.6604181106667, "num" : 10, "question" : "Some of the lesser known actions in this conflict were the bombardment of Solovetsky Monastery in the White Sea and the siege and capture of Kars by the Russians. The Grenadier Guards won out against the Russians at Inkerman, and Lord Raglan led a victorious force at Alma. It also featured a defeat of the Turkish fleet at Sinope, while the Russians expected a land invasion through the Ukrainian Steppes. For 10 points, name this war, which saw a long siege of Sevastopol and the Battle of Balaclava, which featured the infamous Charge of the Light Brigade, on the titular Black Sea peninsula?", "round" : "Round3Final.doc", "seen" : 231, "tournament" : "QuAC I", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2008 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ea68b3d831d6a000422" }, "answer" : "{Rachmaninov’s 2nd} Symphony in {E Minor}, {Opus} 27 (Accept “{Second Symphony}”, “{Symphony No. 2}”, or “{Opus 27}” after {Rachmaninov} is mentioned)", "category" : "Fine Arts", "difficulty" : "Open", "inc_random" : 35.82423872337677, "num" : 6, "question" : "Andre Previn’s 1973 recording of this work was one of the first not to observe the traditional cuts affecting the network of descending scales in the last movement. In the third movement, solos for the English horn and oboe are followed by a cadence in C major and a long silence. In the first movement, the basses and cellos introduce a motto theme that is subsequently played by the solo violin and clarinet. The scherzo starts with the violins accompanying an energetic French horn theme that begins E-A-G-A, while the transition to that movement’s B section is reminiscent of the one that sets up the saxophone solo in its composer’s Symphonic Dances. This work premiered over 10 years after the composer’s previous work in its genre, which had been ruined by the conducting of a drunk Alexander Glazunov. This work was written in Dresden, along with the tone poem The Isle of the Dead. FTP, identify this symphony by Sergei Rachmaninov.", "round" : "PACKET08Lafer.doc", "seen" : 24, "tournament" : "Chicago Open", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ecc8b3d831d6a000cd8" }, "answer" : "{natural logarithm} [accept {natural log} ]", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : 1, "inc_random" : 394.1834704298526, "num" : 33, "question" : "One corollary of the Riemann Hypothesis is that the difference between the logarithmic integral and the prime counting function is upper bounded by the product of the square root function and this function. The first term of the Maclaurin series of this function is x minus 1, and the integral of this function is 1 over x. When this function is applied to a product, it may be written as the sum of this function applied to each term in the product. For 10 points, name this mathematical function, which specifically has base e.", "round" : "districts-05.pdf", "seen" : 259, "tournament" : "HSAPQ VHSL Districts", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3eb98b3d831d6a000873" }, "answer" : "{Oscar Fingal O'Flahertie Wills Wilde}", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : -1, "inc_random" : 359.6421136469581, "num" : 23, "question" : "In one of this man's plays, Sir Robert Chiltern's sister Mabel marries Lord Goring, and in another, Gerald turns out to be the son of Lord Illingworth. Those plays are An Ideal Husband and A Woman of No Importance. The title character of an another of his plays believes her husband is having an affair with Mrs. Erlynne, who is actually her mother. In another play by him, Jack Worthing turns out to be the brother of (*) Algernon Moncrieff. For 10 points, name this author of Lady Windermere's Fan and The Importance of Being Earnest.", "round" : "03.pdf", "seen" : 239, "tournament" : "HSAPQ Tournament 15", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3e998b3d831d6a00015d" }, "answer" : "{Voting Rights} Act of {1965}", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "Open", "fixed" : 1, "inc_random" : 41.53284683753736, "num" : 15, "question" : "One year after its passage, this legislation withstood a direct constitutional challenge in the Katzenbach case. Among the provisions of this legislation was a triggering clause that required federal pre-clearance of procedural changes. This legislation’s second section was amended in 1982 for the purposed of overturning the ruling of the Supreme Court in City of Mobile v. Bolden and employed a “totality of circumstances” approach, while its fourth section was likewise amended in the same year to allow jurisdictions to opt out of coverage if they had been in compliance for the past decade. Pursuant to Section 5 of this legislation, the Justice Department would obtain the right to prosecute such practices as “single-shot,” as a result of the 1969 Allen v. Board of Election decision, and this law’s 8th section provided for federal overseers to make sure that its title practice was not being unconstitutionally restricted. For 10 points, identify this landmark piece of civil rights legislation, which effectively provided for the enforcement of the 15th Amendment.", "round" : "2011-ACFNationals-MinnesotaFinal.doc", "seen" : 27, "tournament" : "ACF Nationals", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3fcb8b3d831d6a0048d9" }, "answer" : "{Lothair} I (or {Lothar} I or {Lotario} I)", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "Open", "inc_random" : 42.29700036952272, "num" : 11, "question" : "This man’s brother in law was the namesake of a French epic titled Girart de Roussillon. A famous loss of this man is described in the poetry of Angelbert, who fought in his army. This husband of Ermengarde of Tours worked with Pope Eugene II to draw up the Constitutio Romano and later revolted against his father in alliance with his brother Pippin. In one agreement, this man received the future Low Countries and the kingdom of Italy. This man was defeated at the Battle of Fontenoy by the forces of two men who had pledged the Oath of Strasbourg. For 10 points, name this son of Louis the Pious, a grandson of Charlemagne who signed the Treaty of Verdun with his brothers Louis the German and Charles the Bald.", "round" : "2011 CO History Bollinger Cheyne.doc", "seen" : 26, "tournament" : "Chicago Open History", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ee48b3d831d6a0012be" }, "answer" : "{Dalai Lamas}", "category" : "Religion", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 392.7670142319985, "num" : 9, "question" : "The death of the fifth of these figures was kept secret for fifteen years to allow for the construction of their official home, the Potala Palace. These figures are discovered by monks who are dispatched to see if children can recognize the objects of their predecessor. They are considered to be manifestations of the bodhisattva Avalokitesvara (AV-ah-loh-kit-ehs-VAH-ra). The fourteenth and current one is known as Tenzin Gyatso and was exiled from Lhassa to India. For 10 points, name this spiritual leaders of Tibetan Buddhism.", "round" : "08.pdf", "seen" : 259, "tournament" : "HSAPQ VHSL States", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3fc88b3d831d6a004835" }, "answer" : "{Angel Falls} [or {Salto Angel}; or {Salto} Churun {Meru}; or {Parakupa-Vena}; or {Kerepakupai Meru}]", "category" : "Geography", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 595.0514504434541, "num" : 6, "question" : "In 1911, this geographical feature was reached by Aleksandrs Laime while, in 1910, this geographical feature had been spotted by Ernesto Sanchez La Cruz. In 1937, while on a search for golden ore, the Flamingo crashed into Auyantepui leading to the immortalization of this geographical feature. Along with Mount Roraima, this three thousand two hundred twelve feet tall geographical feature is found in Canaima National Park. This waterfall forms the Churun River. Falling for two thousand six hundred forty-seven feet, for 10 points, name the world's largest waterfall which is found in Venezuela.", "round" : "DAFT 2009 Round 04 - Edited - Proofread.doc", "seen" : 387, "tournament" : "DAFT", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f6e8b3d831d6a0032dd" }, "answer" : "{Columbia} University [do not accept “{Columbia College}”]", "category" : "Social Science", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : -1, "inc_random" : 337.4683028822765, "num" : 12, "question" : "One longtime professor at this school, who wrote the book Orientalism and was an outspoken advocate for Pales- tinians, was Edward Said. A professor who taught for a long time at this university's highly respected Teachers Col- lege was the author of the books The School and Society and Democracy and Education, John Dewey. One of its current professors, who won the Nobel Prize in Economics, is Joseph Stiglitz. One of its professors, who became known as the Father of American Anthropology, was Franz Boas, and one of his many important students was Margaret Mead. Just before becoming President of the United States, Dwight Eisenhower served as its President, and it awarded a Bachelor's degree in Political Science to Barack Obama. Name this Ivy League university located in New York City.", "round" : "14.pdf", "seen" : 225, "tournament" : "NTSS", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3fe48b3d831d6a004e8b" }, "answer" : "{Jacques Derrida}", "category" : "Philosophy", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 467.0891827249434, "num" : 7, "question" : "This author of an essay on J. L. Austin entitled “Signature Event Context” also engaged with Heidegger in his essay “The Ends of Man.” This author's essay “Cogito and the History of Madness” was collected in a book that also includes a lecture he delivered about “Structure, Sign, and Play.” His best known work introduces the \"hinge,\" the result that there can be no full speech. The former book is Writing and Difference, and the latter sparked a new school of literary theory. For 10 points, name this French-Algerian philosopher who wrote Of Grammatology and founded deconstructionism. ", "round" : "14 HFT (Finals 1).doc", "seen" : 314, "tournament" : "HFT", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f3c8b3d831d6a0026cf" }, "answer" : "{Federalist Papers}", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 56.33489114092663, "num" : 5, "question" : "William Duer was conceived as a contributor to these works, and Samuel Bryan wrote letters in opposition to them. The tenth of these works describes how the union serves as a \"safeguard against domestic faction,\" and the fifty-first states government is \"the greatest of all reflections on human nature,\" and advocates for checks and balances. Written under the pseudonym Publius, they number 85 in total, and were first published in 1787. For 10 points, name these articles by Jay, Madison, and Hamilton that advocate for the ratification of the Constitution.", "round" : "DB 2010 round 11.doc", "seen" : 36, "tournament" : "Delta Burke", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f0a8b3d831d6a001b6e" }, "answer" : "{Rutherford Birchard Hayes}", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 55.44030825863592, "num" : 15, "question" : "As a colonel, this president led a brigade that followed White’s West Virginians in a frontal assault at Cloyd’s Mountain. This president appointed William Woods and John Harlan to the Supreme Court, and faced the Shamokin Uprising and labor unrest in Martinsburg, West Virginia during a large railroad strike in his first year in office. His Treasury Secretary John Sherman launched the Jay Commission, leading this man to remove Alonzo Cornell and (*) Chester Arthur from their positions with the Port of New York. Horace Greeley's fabricated story about an opponent's “Cipher Dispatches” helped this man win an election resolved by Thomas A. Scott. This President saw his veto on the Bland-Allison Act overridden, delighting his foe Roscoe Conkling. For 10 points, name this President whose victory over Samuel Tilden in 1876 led to the end of Reconstruction.", "round" : "FINAL_Harvard+Queens_A.doc", "seen" : 35, "tournament" : "Terrapin Invitational", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3fb68b3d831d6a0043ee" }, "answer" : "An {Enemy} of the {People} [or {En Folkefiende}]", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 45.65026731952094, "num" : 8, "question" : "It begins with the protagonist's wife apologizing for the cold meat offered to a character who describes his boss as a \"chicken-hearted chap, a coward\".  The protagonist notes how he once wrote a favorable article in The Messenger about an entity he later describes as \"the main artery\" and \"nerve center\".  The protagonist's daughter gets fired from her teaching position after her supervisor receives threats, and, besides Petra, Vik fired Captain Horster for providing the main character with a speaking venue.  Other characters include Aslaksen and Billing, two men who work on The People's Herald under Hovstad.  The protagonist is accused by the mayor of writing his inflammatory article because of the will of Morten Kill.  For 10 points, name this Henrik Ibsen play about Dr. Stockmann, a man who finds contaminated water in the town's baths.", "round" : "2009 ACF Regionals - Orth-Bentley.doc", "seen" : 29, "tournament" : "ACF Regionals", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e40368b3d831d6a00620d" }, "answer" : "{Nosferatu}, A {Symphony} of {Horror} [or {Nosferatu}, {eine Symphonie des Grauens}]", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 45.20223535061814, "num" : 15, "question" : "The landscapes of Caspar David Friedrich inspired a scene in this movie in which the lead female character waits for her husband near a sand dune marked by iron crosses. This movie ends with a low-angle shot of a ruined castle being reabsorbed into a mountain, and like The Golem, this movie was scripted by Henrik Galeen. The antagonist of this movie is first encountered by a man who drives through the Land of the Phantoms on the orders of Knock. This movie's antagonist is played by Max Schreck, and follows Hutter to Wisbourg in order to attack Hutter's wife Ellen, only to die upon being pierced by the rays of the sun. For 10 points, name this German expressionist film about Count Orlock, an adaptation of Dracula directed by F. W. Murnau.", "round" : "THUNDER Round 9 - Final.doc", "seen" : 30, "tournament" : "THUNDER", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ebf8b3d831d6a0009f1" }, "answer" : "{Antonio López} de {Santa Anna}", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 344.2064833741169, "num" : 14, "question" : "This man disguised his army as monks while besieged in the convent of Santo Domingo. He duped Isidro Barradas into abandoning Tampico without a fight in Spain's last attempt to retake his country. After losing a leg during the Pastry War, this leader ordered it buried with full military honors. As president, he signed the (*) Treaty of Velaso after a failed attempt to quash a rebellion in a northeast state ended at San Jacinto. For 10 points, name this Mexican general, president, and dictator who commanded the forces that besieged the Alamo.", "round" : "05.pdf", "seen" : 231, "tournament" : "HSAPQ Tournament 16", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3fa48b3d831d6a003fa7" }, "answer" : "archaea", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "Open", "inc_random" : 49.96900309552439, "num" : 2, "question" : "One model organism of this type produces four forms of rhodopsin, including one used to create a proton gradient for ATP synthesis. Another organism of this type uses 2-oxoacid ferredoxin oxidoreductase in place of its missing alpha-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase gene, allowing it to carry out aerobic reactions. That species is Aeropyrum pernix. One group of these organisms uses either acetate or hydrogen as a source of energy, producing a major source of marsh gas as output. Their cell membranes often contain (*) ether-linked lipids and their cell walls lack peptidoglycan. For 10 points, name this domain of organisms which includes methanogens and many extremophiles, which are more closely related to eukaryotes than bacteria.", "round" : "Round 9.doc", "seen" : 33, "tournament" : "VCU Open (Sunday)", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e40528b3d831d6a00688a" }, "answer" : "{Michelangelo's David}", "category" : "Fine Arts", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : -1, "inc_random" : 421.7960075356532, "num" : 11, "question" : "Giorgio Vasari noted that “the Marforio at Rome” is not “equal to it in any respect”, and earlier recalled that its artist pretended to change the nose, heeding a request by Piero Soderini. A wooden framework and rope suspension for it were created by Giuliano da san Gallo and his brother, and it was transported to the Piazza della Signoria. Rossellino was briefly contracted to take it up where Duccio had left, and it drew on the contrapposto of Greek art. For 10 points, name this marble sculpture in Florence by Michelangelo of a figure about to kill Goliath.", "round" : "Round_06_HSAPQ4Q.pdf", "seen" : 276, "tournament" : "HSAPQ 4Q 1", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2008 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3fc68b3d831d6a0047d3" }, "answer" : "{E.M. Forster}", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 45.20711482921615, "num" : 10, "question" : "The narrator of one story by this man finds a one-man cross country race after stopping when his pedometer measures twenty-five, while Kuno is threatened with “Homelessness” by the Machine in another of his stories.  In addition to “The Other Side of the Hedge” and “The Machine Stops”, he wrote about Lilia Herriton, who travels to Tuscany and gets married to Gino Carella in one work, and another of his novels sees Helen Schlegel advise Leonard Bast to quit his job as an insurance clerk, before dying of a heart attack.  For 10 points—name this author of Where Angels Fear to Tread and Howards End, who wrote about Adela Questad's accusations of rape against Dr. Aziz in his novel A Passage to India.", "round" : "8.doc", "seen" : 30, "tournament" : "Chipola Lit + Fine Arts", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ff08b3d831d6a005163" }, "answer" : "{Kingdom} of {Norway} [or {Kongeriket Norge}]", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 343.1307117824908, "num" : 21, "question" : "The Treaty of Kiel ceded this country to Sweden. This country's king Harold Hardrada lost the Battle of Stamford Bridge. This country was traditionally ruled by kings named Haakon. This nation was converted to Christianity under its king St. Olaf. During World War II, this country was led by the Nazi collaborator Vidkun Quisling. For 10 points, name this Scandinavian country whose capital is Oslo.", "round" : "4q2-07.pdf", "seen" : 224, "tournament" : "HSAPQ 4Q2", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e400a8b3d831d6a0057a4" }, "answer" : "{Higgs boson}", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 395.0213706113863, "num" : 22, "question" : "This particle serves as a mediator in the quantum field with which it shares its name, whose nonzero vacuum expectation value allows symmetry breaking. Its mass is estimated to be approximately 140 times that of a proton, has spin zero, and explains the difference between the W and Z bosons and the (*) massless photon, as it is thought to give mass to the gauge photons. The Large Hadron Collider was designed to search for this particle, sometimes called the \"God particle.\" For 10 points, name this particle, the only Standard Model particle yet to be observed.", "round" : "tourn9-04.pdf", "seen" : 266, "tournament" : "HSAPQ Tournament 9", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3eca8b3d831d6a000c63" }, "answer" : "Lolita", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 359.8390097899828, "num" : 19, "question" : "One character in this novel is deeply affected by the death of his childhood friend Annabel Leigh. While the title character of this novel is at summer camp, Charlotte reads another character’s diary before running into the street and being hit by a car. That title character rehearses for a school play written by Clare Quilty after being taken to a New England town by Humbert Humbert. For 10 points, name this Vladimir Nabokov novel about Humbert’s obsession with the underage Dolores Haze.", "round" : "districts-02.pdf", "seen" : 239, "tournament" : "HSAPQ VHSL Districts", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ee88b3d831d6a00139a" }, "answer" : "{Hurricanes} [accept “{tropical cyclones}” for the first sentence and prompt {thereafter}; prompt on “{typhoons}”; do not accept: “{tornadoes}”]", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 65.46212675585411, "num" : 9, "question" : "The CLIPER models use statistical equations to predict zonal and meridional movements in these phenomena. The BAM model predicts their trajectory as a function of the vertically-averaged horizontal wind at shallow, middle, and deep layers, and has a beta parameter corrects for the variation in Coriolis forces with latitude changes. They don’t occur near the equator because of weak Coriolis forces. Stages leading up to them are called tropical depressions and tropical storms, and their intensities are measured on the Saffir Simpson scale.  For 10 points, identify these phenomena which have windspeeds greater than 74 MPH, recent examples of which include Andrew and Katrina.", "round" : "Packet 9 - finalized.doc", "seen" : 43, "tournament" : "MUT", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f098b3d831d6a001b12" }, "answer" : "{Governor} of the {Philippines} [accept equivalents {ie pretty much} any answer {conveying executive authority over} the {Philippines}", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 56.08753631729633, "num" : 7, "question" : "A man who held an earlier form of this position set the precedent for female suffrage by overruling the exclusion of women from local parish councils, though he mostly used this office to amass a fortune in diamond bribes from nefarious Chinese businessmen. Prior to issuing his namesake doctrine as Secretary of State in response to Japan's invasion of Manchuria, Henry Stimson held this post, as did a man who became uncompromisingly genocidal and personally led the butchery of the (*) Moro Crater Rebellion. Theodore Roosevelt chose his Secretary of War based on that man's able administration of this post, held by Arthur MacArthur and Leonard Wood, which in 1942 was assumed by Masuharu Homma after the Battle of Corregidor. Assumed by William H. Taft in the wake of the defeat of Emilio Aguinaldo, for 10 points, name this office tasked with administering a U.S.-controlled island chain with cities like Quezon and Manila.", "round" : "Editors.doc", "seen" : 38, "tournament" : "Terrapin Invitational", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f5d8b3d831d6a002eb5" }, "answer" : "{Pound-Rebka} experiment", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "Open", "inc_random" : 49.27745511918329, "num" : 12, "question" : "The results of this experiment have been confirmed by the experiments of Turneaure, who used 1.42 GHz masers and superconducting-cavity stabilized oscillators. That experiment improved upon the Vessot-Levine experiment that confirmed this experiment using a maser fired on a rocket. Further experiments by one of its namesakes and Snider led to more accurate results for this experiment, and it was performed in a tube filled with helium in order to reduce scattering. Central to this experiment were two (*) iron crystals placed 74 feet apart, one of which served as an emitter of 14.4 KeV gamma rays, and the other of which absorbed the gamma ray. This experiment gave a value for gravitational redshift that was close to values predicted by Einstein's theory. For 10 points, identify this experiment performed by two scientists in the Jefferson Laboratory of Harvard.", "round" : "zFinals 2 - DO NOT READ FOR PRELIMS.doc", "seen" : 32, "tournament" : "Minnesota Open", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f848b3d831d6a003836" }, "answer" : "{Eugene Ionesco}", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 360.2315847531426, "num" : 9, "question" : "This author wrote about the Detective force feeding Choubert stale bread to jog his memory, in Victims of Duty. The title family brings in several incarnations of Roberta, each with a different number of noses, in this author's Jack, or the Submission. He wrote several plays featuring Berenger. In one of his plays, the title event ends with the Professor stabbing the Pupil with an imaginary knife, and in another an old couple arranges the title objects for a speech. In addition to The Lesson and The Chairs, for 10 points name this Absurdist Romanian playwright of The Bald Soprano.", "round" : "Round 07.doc", "seen" : 239, "tournament" : "Prison Bowl", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f0c8b3d831d6a001bd4" }, "answer" : "{Charles Sanders Peirce}", "category" : "Philosophy", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 47.35895156185143, "num" : 12, "question" : "This man argued that chance has an objective status in the universe, a theory known as tychism. In another paper by this thinker, “The Doctrine of Chances,” he maintained that a logical man would be willing to sacrifice his life to save the world and branded social Darwinism “The Gospel of Greed.” This man also dubbed the world of appearances the (*) “phaneron” and claimed that the triadic relation of sign, object, and interpretant necessitated an infinite and evolving sequence of signs. He also proposed three titular universal groupings, “Firstness,” “Secondness,” and “Thirdness,” in his “On a New List of Categories,” and asserted that the scientific method should be used as a basis for the title concept in “The Fixation of Belief.” FTP, identify this author of “How to Make Our Ideas Clear,” an American pragmatist.", "round" : "FINAL_UNC_A+OSU_B+UW_B.doc", "seen" : 30, "tournament" : "Terrapin Invitational", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f218b3d831d6a002061" }, "answer" : "{sarcoplasmic reticulum} [or {SR}; prompt on {endoplasmic reticulum} or {ER}]", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 65.22086682589725, "num" : 1, "question" : "Sodium-mediated antiport membrane proteins in these structures can be passively inhibited through the use of digitalis extracts which block sodium-potassium ATPases. They are mechanically coupled to plasma membrane dihydropyridine receptors. Though not found in neurons, they possess ryanodine receptors which can be activated when phospholipase C cleaves PIP2 into DAG and the signaling molecule inositol trisphosphate. Depending on the cell type, extensions of these structures form dyads or triads with adjacent T-tubules and they contain the protein calsequestrin. For 10 points, name these structures found within muscle cells which store intercellular calcium and are a modified form of an organelle that is continuous with the nuclear envelope and comes in a rough form.", "round" : "2010 - ACF Regionals - Brown + VCU + Oklahoma.doc", "seen" : 43, "tournament" : "ACF Regionals", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f3f8b3d831d6a0027a2" }, "answer" : "Mars", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 65.33549487357959, "num" : 14, "question" : "A meteorite found on this object was the Heat Shield Rock, and this object's namesake Climate Orbiter was lost due to a failed translation of English units into metric units. The astronomer Giovanni Schiaparelli [skyah-pah-REL-lee] created a surface map of this object, which is home to an area of volcanic activity called the Tharsis Ridge. The satellites of this planet were discovered by Asaph Hall, and the color of this planet is due to the mineral hematite. In 2004, the rovers Spirit and Opportunity landed on this planet, which is home to the Solar System's tallest mountain, Olympus Mons. For 10 points, name this red planet whose two moons are Phobos and Deimos.", "round" : "DB 2010 round 9.doc", "seen" : 42, "tournament" : "Delta Burke", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3fa18b3d831d6a003eeb" }, "answer" : "The {Communist Manifesto} [or {Manifest der Kommunistischen Partei}; or {Manifesto} of the {Communist} Party]", "category" : "Philosophy", "difficulty" : "Open", "inc_random" : 40.59798779813573, "num" : 12, "question" : "This work's second section ends with a list of ten measures that will be applicable in most countries, including free education in public schools and the abolition of inheritance rights. It holds that each man must eventually face “his real conditions of life, and his relations with his kind” because “all that is solid melts into air.” Its final section briefly discusses the Social Democrats in France and the Radical party in Switzerland. This work describes hidden interests “lurking” behind law, morality and religion and advocates an association in which (*) “free development of each is the condition for the free development of all.” Its first section notes that “The history of all hitherto existing society is the history of class struggles” and it begins with the phrase “A spectre is haunting Europe.” For 10 points, name this work of Friedrich Engels and Karl Marx.", "round" : "Round 12.doc", "seen" : 25, "tournament" : "VCU Open (Sunday)", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3eb48b3d831d6a00073d" }, "answer" : "{Antoine-Laurent} de {Lavoisier}", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : -1, "inc_random" : 395.5859314689878, "num" : 12, "question" : "This scientist performed an experiment in which he shone the sun’s rays on a diamond, producing carbon dioxide, which showed that diamonds are made of carbon. This author of Essays Physical and Chemical was the first to state the law of conservation of mass, in his Elementary Treatise on Chemistry. He also discredited the (*) phlogiston theory and named oxygen and hydrogen, as well as compiling an early list of elements. For 10 points, name this “father of modern chemistry” who was guillotined during the French Revolution.", "round" : "09.pdf", "seen" : 261, "tournament" : "HSAPQ National History Bowl", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f8b8b3d831d6a0039f0" }, "answer" : "Belarus", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 56.00359750306234, "num" : 5, "question" : "This nation contains a former residence of the Radzivil Family called Mir Castle, and this nation was the home to the Bielski Brothers. This nation's south contains marshes created by the Pripet River and is the source of the Neman River. This nation contains the Bug River and a fortress on that river was the site of the signing of the Treaty of Brest-Litovsk. Containing the city of Mahilyow on the Dneiper River and receiving heavy fallout from the Chernobyl disaster, this nation has been led since 1994 by Alexander Lukashenko. For 10 points, name this former Soviet Republic north of Ukraine sometimes referred to as “White Russia” which has its capital at Minsk.", "round" : "Carleton + UIUC B + Brown - T Party 2010.doc", "seen" : 37, "tournament" : "T-Party", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ec88b3d831d6a000c0d" }, "answer" : "{Saddam Hussein al-Tikriti}", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : -1, "inc_random" : 343.8562164406758, "num" : 11, "question" : "A nuclear facility constructed during the rule of this man was destroyed during Operation Opera. Tariq Aziz was a longtime advisor and international spokesman for this leader. A U.N. program designed to supply his people with humanitarian aid was known as Oil-for-Food. This man's sons Uday and Qusay held high government positions. This man was criticized for using (*) chemical weapons against the Kurdish population following a disastrous invasion of Kuwait. For 10 points, name this ruling leader of the Ba'ath party, the longtime dictator of Iraq.", "round" : "tournament17-14.pdf", "seen" : 229, "tournament" : "HSAPQ Tournament 17", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e400e8b3d831d6a00586a" }, "answer" : "{Jean Jacques Rousseau}", "category" : "Philosophy", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : -1, "inc_random" : 466.9765816736035, "num" : 15, "question" : "One of this man's books states that is better for children to be \"unaware of divinity than to offend it.\" That book contains \"The Profession of a Savoyard Priest,\" and was written by this author of Discourse on the Origin of Inequality. This fan of the \"noble savage\" wrote a didactic novel about an experimental method of education, (*) Emile, and emulated St. Augustine by titling his autobiography Confessions.For 10 points, name this philosopher who explained the concept of the \"general will\" and opined \"Man is born free but everywhere he is in chains\" in his major political work. The Social Contract .", "round" : "tourn9-13.pdf", "seen" : 312, "tournament" : "HSAPQ Tournament 9", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ef38b3d831d6a001609" }, "answer" : "Futurism", "category" : "Fine Arts", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 421.6634639019612, "num" : 4, "question" : "One artist in this movement made photographs like Greetings! influenced by Étienne-Jules Marey. An amorphous red stallion charges while men strain to hold him back in one painting from this movement, The City Rises. One painting from this movement depicts a man lunging forward as he and many others carry (*) black flags. Another work shows a silver chain swinging in four different places while a man’s shoe is seen in several phases of taking a step, as is the title character. Those paintings are Funeral of the Anarchist Galli and Dynamism of a Dog on a Leash. For 10 points, name this artistic movement whose proponents included Carlo Carrà, Giacomo Balla, and Umberto Boccioni and whose manifesto was written by Filippo Marinetti.", "round" : "Packet 14 - Superplayoffs 4.doc", "seen" : 277, "tournament" : "PACE NSC", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3fb48b3d831d6a004347" }, "answer" : "{Andrew Jackson} [or {Old Hickory}]", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 55.61141307814978, "num" : 12, "question" : "During one conflict, this commander captured and executed Alexander Arbuthnot and Robert Ambrister. This man was attacked by the “coffin handbills,” and was known as “Sharp Knife” to Native Americans. This commander defeated Mateo Manrique at the Battle of Pensacola after crushing the Red Sticks. This candidate won a presidential election over William Wirt, and vetoed the Maysville Road bill. He appointed Roger Taney to the Supreme Court, replaced his vice-president during the Peggy Eaton affair, and signed the Indian Removal Act. For 10 points, name this general who defeated John Quincy Adams in the election of 1828, America's seventh president.", "round" : "2009 ACF Regionals - Alabama A + VCU.doc", "seen" : 37, "tournament" : "ACF Regionals", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3e9a8b3d831d6a00017d" }, "answer" : "Pierre {Boulez}", "category" : "Fine Arts", "difficulty" : "Open", "fixed" : 1, "inc_random" : 36.047271782998, "num" : 2, "question" : "This artist conducted a series of concerts in which he filled a concert hall with foam cushions and red rugs. This composer’s longest work ends with a sudden crashing chord just after a soprano whispers the word “mort,” and sets five poems by Stephane Mallarme. He wrote that the composers who developed twelve-tone music killed it by returning to Classical forms in his polemic “Schoenberg is Dead,” and gained prominence after his second piano sonata was premiered by Yvette Grimaud. This composer of Pli selon pli was, along with Karlheinz Stockhausen, the major composer of the Darmstadt School. One of his compositions is scored for alto and six instruments, including guitar, vibraphone, and Xylorimba, features the sections “The Furious Handicraft” and “Executioners of Solitude,” and is based on the poetry of Rene Char. For 10 points, name this avant-garde French composer of The Hammer without a Master.", "round" : "2011-ACFNationals-PennChicagoBCarletonFinal.doc", "seen" : 24, "tournament" : "ACF Nationals", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3edc8b3d831d6a0010c3" }, "answer" : "The {Call} of the {Wild}", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 359.9843773567118, "num" : 4, "question" : "During a trip to Dawson in this work, Hal and Mercedes were criticized for bringing \"blankets for a hotel\" on their journey. Ysabel and Toots were among the companions of this novel's main character during his stay at Judge Miller's Santa Clara home. At the end of this work, the protagonist of this work becomes a legend among the Yeehats. After the murder of John Thornton, the main character of this work decides to leave civilization. For 10 points, name this novel about a canine named Buck, a work by Jack London.", "round" : "26.pdf", "seen" : 233, "tournament" : "HSAPQ VHSL Regular Season", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f2c8b3d831d6a002323" }, "answer" : "{Achaemenid} dynasty [accept word forms]", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "Open", "inc_random" : 41.18210738501512, "num" : 12, "question" : "One member of this dynasty was said to have murdered his brother Bardiya, who would later be impersonated by Gaumata the Magician in a revolt against that ruler. This dynasty claimed descent via two lines from an ancestor named Teispes, and the founder of the elder line of this dynasty first came to power as the ruler of Anshan. Architectural achievements of this dynasty include the construction of the Hall of One Hundred Columns, and a member of this dynasty sent Scylax of Caryanda on an expedition to India. Another member of this dynasty founded a similarly named dynasty which became the 27th dynasty of Egypt following his victory at the battle of Pelusium. One of this dynasty's major capitals was at Pasargadae, and it became extinct following the murder of its last ruler by Bessus after that ruler had lost to Alexander the Great at Gaugamela. A famous ruler of this dynasty overthrew Astyages to take control of the Median empire, while its younger branch included the father-in-law of Mardonius and author of the Behistun inscription, as well as a king who crossed the Hellespont before losing at the battle of Salamis. Including such rulers as two kings named Cambyses and a pair of Cyruses, for ten points, identify this dynasty of ancient Iran whose other members included Darius the Great and Xerxes I.", "round" : "2010 - Chicago Open - Round 01 - The Solid Scholars.doc", "seen" : 29, "tournament" : "Chicago Open", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ec38b3d831d6a000ad2" }, "answer" : "{Franklin Delano Roosevelt} [or {FDR}; prompt on {Roosevelt}]", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : -1, "inc_random" : 343.8669678324368, "num" : 9, "question" : "Elizabeth Shoumatoff was painting a portrait of this man at his death. He borrowed a phrase from playwright Robert Sherwood in giving the \"Arsenal of Democracy\" speech. Another speech inspired a Norman Rockwell painting by listing the Four Freedoms. This man's first Inaugural Address asserted that \"the (*) only thing we have to fear is fear itself,\" and another speech labeled December 7 as a \"date which will live in infamy.\" For 10 points, name this Fireside chatter and four term Democratic president who presided over the New Deal and American entrance into World War II.", "round" : "15.pdf", "seen" : 225, "tournament" : "HSAPQ Tournament 16", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f7e8b3d831d6a0036ae" }, "answer" : "{Friedrich Ludwig Gottlob Frege}", "category" : "Philosophy", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 48.30929072829895, "num" : 15, "question" : "He differentiated between things or descriptions that can have the same denotation but different senses in one paper, and in another work by this man, he states that in an expression, the title things are linked by the presence of a helping verb, which leads to the problem signified by the namesake “horse” of one of those things. His namesake theorem describes how Hume's Principle can derive the five Dedekind/Peano axioms, and he argued in this most famous work that a statement about a phenomenon's number reveals something about the phenomenon's conception. He wrote a text subtitled a “logico-mathematical enquiry into the concept of number” and two others called On Sense and Reference and Concept and Object. For 10 points, name this German philosopher of logic who wrote Concept Script and The Foundations of Arithmetic.", "round" : "ColumbiaA.doc", "seen" : 32, "tournament" : "Princeton Buzzerfest", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e40198b3d831d6a005ae8" }, "answer" : "Battle of {Saratoga} [accept {Bemis Heights} or {Freeman's Farm} before mentioned]", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 55.55138791003264, "num" : 15, "question" : "The losing army in this battle was hampered by an inability to rendezvous with Colonel Barry St. Leger's force of mostly Iroquois Indians. The retreating army at this battle paused to bury one of their generals, Simon Fraser, who had been killed the previous day. The losing commander, fresh off a retaking of Fort Ticonderoga, never received aid from Henry Clinton and was defeated when enemy reinforcements under Benedict Arnold arrived. For 10 points, name this battle which took place in September and October 1777, in which American forces under Horatio Gates defeated John Burgoyne's British forces, fought at Bemis Heights and Freeman's Farm.", "round" : "MUT II - Minnesota 1.doc", "seen" : 35, "tournament" : "MUT", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ec18b3d831d6a000a57" }, "answer" : "{sine} function", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : -1, "inc_random" : 395.1843905327842, "num" : 1, "question" : "Niven's Theorem concerns the values taken by this function on certain rational inputs. This function is used to represent the imaginary part of a complex number when converting to polar coordinates and is denoted with the hyperbolic function e to the x minus e to the negative x divided by two. The Taylor series for this function is equal to zero when x equals zero and the inverse of this function is the (*) cosecant function. For 10 points, name this function which for an angle alpha of a triangle is equal to the ratio of opposite over hypotenuse.", "round" : "10.pdf", "seen" : 259, "tournament" : "HSAPQ Tournament 16", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ec18b3d831d6a000a3f" }, "answer" : "A {Clockwork Orange}", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 359.5189224488568, "num" : 23, "question" : "Near the end of this novel, the protagonist listens to music by Otto Skadelig before jumping out of a window. During a burglary the protagonist is betrayed by Dim and is sent to prison where he kills an inmate who complained too much; as punishment, he is forced to watch violent films after taking drugs that make him feel ill. Words such as “rooker” and “droog” are part of this novel’s language (*) Nadsat, which is spoken by the subject of the Ludovico Technique, Alex. Adapted into a film by Stanley Kubrick, name, for 10 points, this novel by Anthony Burgess.", "round" : "08.pdf", "seen" : 244, "tournament" : "HSAPQ Tournament 16", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3e9f8b3d831d6a0002a3" }, "answer" : "{Trung} sisters", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "College", "fixed" : 1, "inc_random" : 55.74026672863401, "num" : 21, "question" : "This group was opposed by a general who had earned the nickname “Queller of the Deep” for his previous crushing of rebellions among the Nanman peoples. According to one account, this group became politically active after one of their spouses was executed by Governor To, the commander of the Wangku Commandary, who this group successfully expelled. The movement led by this group collapsed after they ordered a retreat behind the Jin River, after which this group drowned themselves in the Hat river. This group led a three year rebellion against the occupying Han dynasty. For 10 points, name these sisters who led an anti-Chinese rebellion in Vietnam.", "round" : "ACF Regionals 2011 - Georgetown and ASU A final.doc", "seen" : 75, "tournament" : "ACF Regionals", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f698b3d831d6a003186" }, "answer" : "Good {Friday} [accept {Holy Friday} or {Great Friday}]", "category" : "Religion", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : -1, "inc_random" : 392.9987476090901, "num" : 8, "question" : "The Troparion of this day sees an angel tell some \"myrrh-bearing women\" that myrrh is not good enough for Christ. One event on this day saw a speech in which crying women were told to “weep for yourselves and for your children,” and that barren women would be blessed one day. Events during it can be represented by the Via Dolorosa, which honors the actions of Saint Veronica and Simon of Cyrene. This day immediately follows another holiday which contains the traditional washing of the feet and is given the adjective “Maundy.” For 10 points, name this holiday which commemorates the day Jesus was crucified and takes place two days before Easter Sunday.", "round" : "6.pdf", "seen" : 266, "tournament" : "NASAT", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ea68b3d831d6a000425" }, "answer" : "{virial} equation of state", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "Open", "fixed" : 1, "inc_random" : 48.9513207571581, "num" : 9, "question" : "The coefficients of this equation in the limit of infinite volume are obtained by performing cluster integrals, a formalism extended to quantum systems by Kahn and Uhlenbeck. For a classical system, the second coefficient in this equation is typically evaluated by assuming the Lennard-Jones intermolecular potential and integrating with respect to radius the quantity “one minus the negative exponent of the potential, times radius squared.” If the hard sphere potential is assumed instead, the result is identical to the van der Waals equation. This equation gives the product of pressure and volume per particle as a power series in the cube of the thermal wavelength over the volume per particle. FTP, identify this equation of state, an expansion whose namesake coefficients are functions of temperature.", "round" : "PACKET08Lafer.doc", "seen" : 33, "tournament" : "Chicago Open", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f698b3d831d6a003197" }, "answer" : "Battle of {Flodden Field}", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : -1, "inc_random" : 344.3889468375128, "num" : 2, "question" : "Before this battle, one side had captured Norham, Etal and Ford Castles causing another side to make their approach via Twizel Bridge. Archers arriving through Crookham Dene provided supporting action during one part of this battle. One side in this battle had honored their Auld Alliance with France's Louis XII as the opposing side was allied with Spain and the Papal States in the War of the League of Cambrai. Sometimes known as the Battle of Braxton, one side in this battle was led by Thomas Howard, Earl of Surrey while another side saw the death of their leader James IV. For 10 points, name this decisive 1513 English victory over the Scots.", "round" : "7.pdf", "seen" : 228, "tournament" : "NASAT", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ebb8b3d831d6a000908" }, "answer" : "Las {Meninas} [accept The {Maids} of {Honor} before mentioned]", "category" : "Fine Arts", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 421.9756126282737, "num" : 11, "question" : "Mariana of Austria is one figure that can be seen in this painting, which also includes a man pausing in the background on a flight of stairs and a large brown dog resting in the bottom front right. In the background, two figures of royalty can be seen reflected in a mirror. This painting shows a scene inside the Alcazar palace of Philip IV; to the far left is the painter himself working on a large canvas while in the center a group of servants, or ladies in waiting, attend to the (*) Infanta Margarita. For 10 points, name this painting by Diego Velazquez whose title translates as “The Maids of Honor”.", "round" : "10.pdf", "seen" : 285, "tournament" : "HSAPQ Tournament 15", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f048b3d831d6a001a1c" }, "answer" : "{Dungeons} and {Dragons} [accept {DnD}]", "category" : "Trash", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : -1, "inc_random" : 847.3463064476382, "num" : 13, "question" : "This game was banned by Wisconsin’s Wapun prison after a prisoner said that players were forming a gang and developing escape fantasies. Additions to this game that add new content are called splatbooks, and it was subject to a moral panic, including a tract condemning it by Jack Chick and an incident involving a suicide attempt in a steam tunnel. Monsters unique to this game include the beholder and mind flayer. It is played with [*] twenty-sided dice, and its games are overseen by a referee called the Dungeon Master. For 10 points, name this popular tabletop role-playing game created by Dave Arneson and Gary Gygax.", "round" : "Round 10.doc", "seen" : 565, "tournament" : "St. Anselms and Torrey Pines", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f4c8b3d831d6a002ad2" }, "answer" : "{Ashoka} [accept {Asoka}; prompt “{Devanampriya Priyadarsi}”, prompt “{Dhamma}”]", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 344.4056530848611, "num" : 5, "question" : "This ruler subdued a minor revolt in the city of Taxila. His name means “without sorrow” in his native language, and he ruled from the region of Maghda.  He erected a sculpture featuring a namesake 24-spoke [*] ‘wheel of righteousness' and four outward-facing lions at Sarnath, and many his Rock and Pillar Edicts still stand. He conquered the Kalinga Empire, and this grandson of Chandragupta's conversion to pacifist Buddhism greatly aided that religion's spread.  For 10 points, which Mauryan Emperor ruled India from 273 to 232 BCE?", "round" : "Ben Cooper 2010 Packet 5 COMPLETE.docx", "seen" : 229, "tournament" : "GDS Ben Cooper Memorial", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f9f8b3d831d6a003e86" }, "answer" : "{enolate} [prompt on {alcohol} or {alkene}, since {both} are {parts} of an {enol}]", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "Open", "inc_random" : 49.21415623347275, "num" : 21, "question" : "A naturally occurring anti-HIV chemical called Lancifodilactone G contains an unusually stable example of this functional group. One of these is produced as the penultimate step of a version of the Oxy-Cope rearrangement, and the reaction of that compound provides the driving force of the reaction. Another one is formed in an unfavorable step in the Mannich reaction. An ester is converted to one of these before reacting with a second ester in the first step of the Claisen condensation, and one of these reacts with the carbonyl of an aldehyde or ketone as a key intermediate in the aldol addition. For 10 points, name this functional group which can be formed by the deprotonation of a beta carbon and protonation of a carbonyl, a tautomer of an aldehyde of ketone.", "round" : "The Finals 1.doc", "seen" : 32, "tournament" : "VCU Open (Saturday)", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3e9c8b3d831d6a0001ff" }, "answer" : "Battle of {Bunker Hill} [accept {Battle} of {Breed's Hill} before it is read]", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "College", "fixed" : 1, "inc_random" : 55.20738459480926, "num" : 9, "question" : "Two weeks before this battle, the attacking force acquired three more generals with the arrival of the frigate Cerberus. Part of the defending force was led by Thomas Knowlton, who encouraged his men to take cover behind a rail fence. Men killed during this battle included a physician from the Committee of Correspondence, Joseph Warren, who appears in the painting of this battle by John Trumbull. Either of the defending leaders, William Prescott and Israel Putnam, may have issued the noted command “don't fire until you see the whites of their eyes.” For 10 points, William Howe's British forces sustained more than a thousand casualties in what June 1775 battle near Boston that was actually fought on Breed's Hill?", "round" : "ACF Regionals 2011 - Berkeley and Miami C final.doc", "seen" : 48, "tournament" : "ACF Regionals", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3fc48b3d831d6a00474c" }, "answer" : "{Great Expectations}", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 46.34357499238104, "num" : 1, "question" : "One character in this work is a \"pale young gentleman\" who has an affair with a woman named Ciara, and shares an apartment with the protagonist of this work after attempting to fight him the first time they meet.  Another character in this work adopts the stage name Mr. Waldengarver when he quits his job as a clerk of the church to pursue an acting career.  In addition to Mr. Wopsle, one character in this work is married to Belinda and tutors Starpop, Bentley Drummle, and the lover of Ciara, Herbert Pocket.  The protagonist of this work falls in love with Estella, even though she has warned him that her ability to love was ruined by Miss Havisham.  For 10 points—name this work about Phillip Pirrip, or \"Pip\", a bildungsroman by Charles Dickens.", "round" : "2.doc", "seen" : 31, "tournament" : "Chipola Lit + Fine Arts", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e40138b3d831d6a005998" }, "answer" : "{Orpheus} in the {Underworld} (accept {Orphée aux Enfers})", "category" : "Fine Arts", "difficulty" : "Open", "inc_random" : 36.12157363072038, "num" : 5, "question" : "In this opera's second act, one character sings “I'm feeling all lonely and shivery” to a baritone whose part consists only of buzzing in the “Fly Duet.” The soprano is bored listening to one character's endless stories of his former role as the King of Boetia, and earlier the soprano argued death is not terrible in the aria, “La mort m'apparaît souriante” after being led to a cornfield where she was bitten by a snake before the shepherd Aristee's transformation. The character of Public Opinion coerces the protagonist into seeking his wife, who sneaks into a party disguised as a bacchante in this opera's final scene before Jupiter's attempts to lead a minuet fail as the party dances the “Galop Infernal,” which provides the tune for the “Can-Can.” For 10 points, name this opera satirizing Gluck in which the titular bard descends to the domain of Pluto to find his wife Eurydice, composed by Jacques Offenbach.", "round" : "KLEE - Round 2.doc", "seen" : 25, "tournament" : "Minnesota Open KLEE Fine Arts", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e402a8b3d831d6a005f51" }, "answer" : "the {Pyrenees} or {los Pirineos} or {les Pyrénées} or {els Pirineus} or {los Pirenèus} or {Perinés} or {Pirinioak}", "category" : "Geography", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : -1, "inc_random" : 594.3396229967475, "num" : 14, "question" : "Cap de Creus is on the eastern end of this mountain range, where bandits who kill St. Aubert in The Mysteries of Udolpho live. A range on the Moon named for it separates Mare Nectaris and the Sea of Tranquility, and The Stone Raft deals with events caused by a crack in it. The location of Cirque de Gavarnie, a treaty named for this range was signed after the Battle of the Dunes and provided for the marriage of Maria Theresa and Louis XI. Roncevaux Pass, where Roland dies, is in it. With highest point at Aneto, for 10 points, name this mountain range that encompasses Andorra, and separates Spain and France.", "round" : "Packet 1.doc", "seen" : 390, "tournament" : "Prison Bowl", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f078b3d831d6a001ab1" }, "answer" : "{bystander} effect [accept “{Kitty Genovese syndrome}” before “{Genovese}”]", "category" : "Social Science", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 337.574428392807, "num" : 16, "question" : "A variant on this effect was observed in a rope-pulling experiment conducted by Max Ringelmann. This effect was first demonstrated in 1968 by Darley and Latane. In one experiment on this effect, participants completed questionnaires while a room filled with smoke. This effect’s causes include [*] pluralistic ignorance, deference to qualified authority, and diffusion of responsibility. Good Samaritan laws combat this effect, which was observed during Winton Moseley’s murder of Kitty Genovese. For 10 points, identify this psychological effect that results in a reduced likelihood of one person helping another when in a group of observers.", "round" : "Round 6.doc", "seen" : 230, "tournament" : "St. Anselms and Torrey Pines", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3fa68b3d831d6a00403f" }, "answer" : "{Shaka} Zulu", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 56.06315255793743, "num" : 4, "question" : "Nathaniel Isaacs wrote an account of this ruler, who established his capital at Bulawayo. This ruler invented the Iklwa, a shorter version of the assegai, and he defeated Zwide at the Battle of Gqokli Hill by using his “buffalo horns” formation. This man ordered the milk in his empire to be drained away after the death of his mother Nandi; after Nandi's death, this ruler massacred over 7,000 of his own subjects which led his brother Dingane to assassinate him. Earlier he had united the Mthethwa and Ndwandwe peoples after succeeding Dingiswayo. For 10 points, name this brilliant tactician who united his people and founded the Zulu Kingdom in the early nineteenth century.", "round" : "2009 ACF Fall edited - Duke A + Harvard Zhao.doc", "seen" : 37, "tournament" : "ACF Fall", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ede8b3d831d6a001132" }, "answer" : "apostrophe", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 359.8699572955724, "num" : 18, "question" : "George Bernard Shaw referred to these things as \"uncouth bacilli\" and led a campaign to limit their use. This term is also used to refer to a rhetorical trope found in Edgar Allan Poe's \"To Science\" in which a speaker \"turns away\" to address a personification or abstract concept which is not physically present. For 10 points, name this figure of speech which shares its name with a punctuation mark used to indicate the possessive case and to create contractions.", "round" : "29.pdf", "seen" : 246, "tournament" : "HSAPQ VHSL Regular Season", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f588b3d831d6a002da0" }, "answer" : "{Donald Barthelme} [prompt on partial answer]", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "Open", "inc_random" : 31.00892494642176, "num" : 15, "question" : "This author wrote of a group of friends planning the elaborate hanging of a man who had “gone too far” in his story “Some of Us Had Been Threatening Our Friend Colby”. He also wrote a story in which The President takes a sledgehammer to a sculpture called Season's Greetings, one of many unusual things that happen after Peterson agrees to appear on the game show Who Am I?. The narrator of another of his stories reminisces about fixing a bicycle seat for his child, who he otherwise resents, and about breaking his nine-cocktail rule during a fight with his Elle-obsessed wife Wanda. This author of “A Shower of Gold” and (*) “Critique de la Quotidienne” also published the collection Come Back, Dr. Caligari and such novels as The King, The Dead Father, and the fairy-tale adaptation Snow White. For 10 points, identify this American author of such collections of “flash fiction” as Forty Stories and Sixty Stories, the brother of fellow authors Steven and Frederick.", "round" : "Round 01 - Chicago A.doc", "seen" : 21, "tournament" : "Minnesota Open", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3fe38b3d831d6a004e37" }, "answer" : "bone", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 395.2139920215122, "num" : 7, "question" : "This tissue is weakened in a condition that presents Harrison's groove, and parathyroid hormone promotes its resorption. Perforated by Volkmann's and Haversian canals, this tissue's inorganic component is in the form of hydroxyapatite. Generally forming structures with a thinner diaphysis and wider epiphysis, this tissue is weakened by the vitamin D deficiency rickets and another resulting from low alpha-estrogen levels. For 10 points, name this calcium-rich tissue created by osteoblasts and destroyed by osteoclasts that makes up the skeletal system.", "round" : "10 HFT.doc", "seen" : 265, "tournament" : "HFT", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ef28b3d831d6a0015b1" }, "answer" : "{Salem witch trials} [prompt on {alleged acts} of {witchcraft} in {Salem} or equivalents]", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 343.2787628832739, "num" : 5, "question" : "Robert Calef and Thomas Brattle offered contemporary criticism of these events in More Wonders of the Invisible World. One participant in these events tested the “effluvia” theory by feeding a dog a cake with urine baked into it. Biologist Linnda Caporael claims they coincided with the consumption of infected rye bread. William Stoughton presided over these events during William Phips’s governorship. They started after doctor (*) William Griggs provided treatment for certain hysterical fits, and “spectral evidence” during these events was allowed by Cotton Mather. Participants in these events included Betty Parris and Abigail Williams, and during these events stones were piled on Giles Corey. A slave named Tituba was also implicated in these events. For 10 points, name these 1692 Massachusetts events in which many accused heretics were killed with little evidence.", "round" : "Packet 10 - Playoffs 5.doc", "seen" : 232, "tournament" : "PACE NSC", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ebc8b3d831d6a000950" }, "answer" : "{Tom Jones} [accept either name]", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 360.5965776159428, "num" : 14, "question" : "This character convinces Nightingale to stay together with his lover Nancy while living in London. There, this man has an affair with Lady Bellaston. This character comes to London after learning he is not the father of Molly Seagrim’s child. After it is revealed that this student of Thwackum is one of Bridget’s sons, he realizes that his rival, Blifil, is his half-brother, and his guardian, Squire (*) Allworthy, is his uncle. Name this lover of Sophia Western, a foundling whose history is recounted in a Henry Fielding novel.", "round" : "13.pdf", "seen" : 238, "tournament" : "HSAPQ Tournament 15", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3faf8b3d831d6a00422b" }, "answer" : "{Ivan Sergeyevich Turgenev}", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "Open", "inc_random" : 31.13854059576989, "num" : 9, "question" : "In one of this author's stories, a physician married an \"ill-tempered woman\" who does nothing but sleep in order to punish himself for falling in love with Alexandra, a dying maiden. In addition to \"The District Doctor,\" this man wrote a novel in which the protagonist's plan to marry Liza is thwarted when he finds his purportedly dead wife, Varvara Pavlova, waiting for him in the foyer. In another of his novels, the titular friend of Lezhnev impresses the household of Darya Mikhailovna and falls in love with Natasha. Vassily Vassilevitch goes to Alexander Mikhalyich's dinner party in this man's story \"Hamlet of the Shchigrovsky District,\" and this man wrote about Elena's fascination with the Bulgarian Insarov in On the Eve. Another work by this author of The Home of the Gentry and Rudin discusses the dissection of a frog and a man's death from cutting himself with an infected knife during surgery. For 10 points, name this Russian author of The Sportsman's Sketches who created Kirsanov and Bazarov and Fathers and Sons.", "round" : "r10- Dartmouth-Truman State.doc", "seen" : 20, "tournament" : "ACF Nationals", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f478b3d831d6a002990" }, "answer" : "{Islamic Republic} of {Pakistan}", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : -1, "inc_random" : 343.8205746589229, "num" : 18, "question" : "One leader of this country executed his predecessor Zulfikar Ali; that ruler Zia ul-Haq, funded A.Q. Khan's nuclear research. Its first Governor-General was Muhammed Ali Jinnah of the Muslim League, and in 1971, its “East” exclave became Bangladesh. In 2007, its former leader Benazir Bhutto was assassinated, and its Swat valley contains Taliban fighters. For 10 points, name this country home to Pervez Musharraf, which has fought over Kashmir with India.", "round" : "Packet 13.doc", "seen" : 228, "tournament" : "Fall Novice", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e40498b3d831d6a00666b" }, "answer" : "{Hartree-Fock} (3) theory or model or method or {equation} [prompt on \"{Self-consistent field}\" until mentioned; do not accept \"{Hartree method}\"]", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 66.64216468739323, "num" : 4, "question" : "A program developed by Polish scientists uses a Cartesian deformed harmonic-oscillator to perform calculations when Skyrme interactions are considered along with it. The Kohn-Sham equations calculate the quantity associated with it but use the density functional theory instead. The Hall-Roothaan equations are linear combinations of basis functions used in this model and the Møller-Plesset improvement to it incorporates correlation to the operator that is formed after each iteration of the procedure. The introduction of Slater determinants to this theory addressed its inability to account for the antisymmetry principle and it assumes the ? Born-Oppenheimer approximation. It exists in restricted, restricted open-shell, and unrestricted varieties based on the spin and the existence of singly occupied orbitals. For 10 points, identify this self consistent field method which approximates the ground state energy of an N-body system, named for a British and a Russian physicist.", "round" : "Gaddis - Round 8.doc", "seen" : 44, "tournament" : "Gaddis I", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2008 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ecf8b3d831d6a000d9f" }, "answer" : "{linked} list [prompt on {list}; or {free list} before \"{circular}\" is read]", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 394.1708427809644, "num" : 28, "question" : "The CAR and CDR operators work on this data structure. It's not a tree, but this structure may include sentinel nodes. It can be used to implement a stack efficiently since inserting and removing the first element takes constant time. In the worst case it will take Big-O of n time to insert and remove elements from an n-element instance of this data structure. For 10 points name this type of list which in which each data entry is associated with a pointer to the next item in the list.", "round" : "regionals-03.pdf", "seen" : 270, "tournament" : "HSAPQ VHSL Regionals", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f068b3d831d6a001a82" }, "answer" : "{Gobi} Desert", "category" : "Geography", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : -1, "inc_random" : 594.5970408536959, "num" : 10, "question" : "The Alashan Plateau sits to the southwest of this region’s Eastern steppe, and the first fossilized dinosaur eggs were discovered in the Bayanhongor (“buy-an-hon-gore”) area of this region. Home to the only known desert-dwelling bear, this region is bound by the Altai mountains to the north and is the native habitat of the [*] Bactrian camel. The Tian Shan range acts as a border between this region’s Dzungarian (“zun-gay-ree-an”) Basin and the Taklamakan Desert to the west. Ulanbataar is located in this desert, flanked by the Tibetan plateau to the south. For 10 points, name this large rain-shadow desert bordering Mongolia and China.", "round" : "Round 4.doc", "seen" : 400, "tournament" : "St. Anselms and Torrey Pines", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3e9f8b3d831d6a0002b2" }, "answer" : "Pope {Pius IX} [or {Pio Nono}; prompt on {Pius}]", "category" : "Philosophy", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 47.37723310175352, "num" : 15, "question" : "In one tract, this man made a repeated distinction between true and false civilization, warning that merely moving forward is not progress. A contemporary thinker described the later treatise Joy and Hope as the “counter” to this man’s most noted writing. He responded to the withdrawal of the French military from his lands and condemned the supremacy of state law and natural liberty in Quanta Cura. He also called Freemasonry the “synagogue of Satan” and attacked the Kulturkampf in an index of condemned statements, the Syllabus of Errors. This man became the “prisoner of the Vatican” when he refused to accept Italian unification. For 10 points, name this man who defined the dogma of immaculate conception and convened Vatican I, the longest-reigning Pope.", "round" : "ACF Regionals 2011 - Maryland A and Boise State final.doc", "seen" : 29, "tournament" : "ACF Regionals", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f638b3d831d6a003023" }, "answer" : "{Vasco da Gama}", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 344.0325041334145, "num" : 21, "question" : "This man threatened the amir Ibrahim with burning down Kilwa, and he formed alliances with the rulers of Cochin and Cannanore to combar the Zamorin of Calicut. This man was honored with the founding of the Jeronimos monastery in Belem, and this man ordered the Sao Rafael to be burned near Malindi. He erected pillars known as padraos at locations such as the Rio dos Bons Sinais, and King Manuel I commissioned Pedro Alvares Cabral's expedition following this man's successes. This man was named viceroy in India in 1524. For 10 points, name this Portuguese explorer who opened trade routes from Western Europe to the East Indies via the Cape of Good Hope.", "round" : "1.pdf", "seen" : 233, "tournament" : "NASAT", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3fc38b3d831d6a004726" }, "answer" : "“Chicago”", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 45.71114305686206, "num" : 5, "question" : "The title character of this work is observed \"Laughing even as an ignorant fighter laughs who has never lost a battle\" and who is as \"Fierce as a dog with tongue lapping for action\".  Earlier, that character was seen \"flinging magnetic curses amid the toil of piling job on job\" and \"with lifted head singing so proud to be alive and coarse and strong and cunning\".  The narrator of this work admits, \"it is true I have seen the gunman kill and go free and kill again\", and tells the title character \"I have seen your painted women under the gas lamps luring the farm boys\".  This work opens by describing the title character as \"Hog Butcher for the World, Tool Maker, Stacker of Wheat\".  For 10 points—name this work about an American city, a poem by Carl Sandburg.", "round" : "1.doc", "seen" : 30, "tournament" : "Chipola Lit + Fine Arts", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ea78b3d831d6a000432" }, "answer" : "{Sunga} Dynasty", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "Open", "fixed" : 1, "inc_random" : 42.55825010873377, "num" : 2, "question" : "The architectural achievements of this dynasty include erecting the Gateways of Bharhut Stupa, and its ninth king erected the \"Heliodorus pillar,\" which attests to the visit of a Greek diplomat to this empire. Its founder employed the philosopher Patanjali as a guide, who authored the Yoga Sutras - that founder allegedly persecuted Buddhists and warred with king Menander of Bactria. The final ruler of this empire was overthrown by Vasudeva, who set up the short-lived Kanva Dynasty. The first ruler of this dynasty ascended by killing Brithadratha at a military parade and ruled for 36 years - that king Pushyamitra then gave way to his son, who was the subject of a play by Kalidasa - that son was Agnimitra. FTP, name this dynasty founded in 185 B.C. after the collapse of the Mauryan Empire.", "round" : "PACKET09Editor2.doc", "seen" : 29, "tournament" : "Chicago Open", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3eec8b3d831d6a001472" }, "answer" : "{simple harmonic oscillator} [or {SHO}; or {simple harmonic} motion; or {SHM}; or {mass-on-a-}", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : -1, "inc_random" : 394.358637309866, "num" : 8, "question" : "One deviation from this ideal system is mathematically described by an equation that includes a term\n proportional to the cube of position, where the proportionality constant is less than zero in the \"soft\" case.\n That equation is the Duffing equation. Another deviation from this ideal system is mathematically\n described by an equal that includes a term proportional to the time derivative of position, where the\n proportionality constant is known as the damping coefficient. This system itself is described by a\n second-order differential equation formed by equating Newton's Second Law and Hooke's Law. For 10\n points, sinusoidal motion is typical of what kind of system exemplified by pendulums and\n masses-on-springs?", "round" : "08.pdf", "seen" : 262, "tournament" : "NASAT", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e405d8b3d831d6a006b52" }, "answer" : "{Saint Flavius Valerius Aurelius Constantinus} I [or {Constantine} the {Great}; prompt on “{Constantine}”]", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 343.9777678928804, "num" : 21, "question" : "This man was victorious at Chrysopolis when his enemy forbade his own troops from looking at this man’s standard. This man had Maximian strangled and defeated Licinius, bringing an end to the Tetrarchy. He crushed the Donatists and called the Council of Nicea. This man supposedly gave land in Italy to [*] Pope Sylvester in his “Donation,” and this man was shown the labarum, or chi-ro, and told “In this sign, you shall conquer” before defeating Maxentius at the Battle of Milvian Bridge. For 10 points name this issuer of the Edict of Milan, who settled in Byzantium and renamed it for himself, the first Christian Roman Emperor.", "round" : "Round 11.doc", "seen" : 228, "tournament" : "St. Anselms and Torrey Pines", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3e948b3d831d6a00003e" }, "answer" : "{Suzuki-Miyaura coupling} [or {Suzuki-Miyaura} reaction; or {SM coupling}]", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "Open", "inc_random" : 49.87910780869424, "num" : 12, "question" : "Baudoin developed an efficient one-pot way to generate ortho- substituted products based on this reaction, while Beller developed a technique using diadamantyl-n-butylphosphane ligands to carry out this reaction using in situ formed complex catalysts. A group including Kim, Lee, and Hyeon developed a version of this reaction that used hollow silica spheres to create spherical recyclable heterogeneous catalysts of a certain metal. This reaction is commonly used for macrocylicization in the synthesis of Rutamycin B. Sodium carbonate and potassium carbonate are commonly used in this reactionfor activation of one reagent for the transmetallation step. Nickel can be used as a catalyst for a version of this reaction for aryl chlorides. The mechanism of this reaction is somewhat similar to the Stille reaction, and it is an efficient way in a synthesis to create carbon-carbon bonds between two aryls. The traditional catalyst consists of four triphenylphosphines bound to a certain metal. For 10 points, name this palladium-catalyzed reaction that couples aryl boronic acids and aryl halides.", "round" : "2011-ACFNationals-ChicagoCUVAMarylandFinal.doc", "seen" : 35, "tournament" : "ACF Nationals", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3fe98b3d831d6a004fc6" }, "answer" : "Ernest Miller {Hemingway} [accept \"{Hills} Like {White Elephants}\" before \"{this author}\" is read]", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : -1, "inc_random" : 359.612831395911, "num" : 24, "question" : "Jig and \"The American\" drink Anis del Toro in a Madrid train station in this author's \"Hills Like White Elephants,\" which appears in the collection Men Without Women along with some Nick Adams stories, such as \"The Killers.\" In one of this author's novels, the narrator walks home in the rain after Catherine Morland delivers a stillborn baby. This man wrote about Michael Campbell's engagement to Lady Brett Ashley in Pamplona in a work narrated by Jake Barnes, and in another work, Manolin is apprenticed to a fisherman who idolizes Joe DiMaggio, Santiago. For 10 points, name this author of A Farewell to Arms, The Sun Also Rises, and The Old Man and the Sea.", "round" : "4q1-09.pdf", "seen" : 242, "tournament" : "HSAPQ 4Q1", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f348b3d831d6a002503" }, "answer" : "“{Frost} at {Midnight}”", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "Open", "inc_random" : 31.10303051024676, "num" : 10, "question" : "This poem describes an “idling Spirit” which searches for mirrors of itself everywhere and “makes a toy of thought.” The speaker of this poem pretended to study his books while he was actually lost in thought, but notes that when his door opened, “I snatched / A hasty glance, and still my heart leaped up / For still I hoped to see the stranger’s face.” Its speaker recalls “my sweet birthplace, and the old church tower / Whose bells, the poor man’s only music, rang / from morn to evening,” and is disappointed that he grew up “In the great city, pent ‘mid cloisters dim,” but takes comfort in the prospect of his son growing up in the countryside. The speaker broods over a film fluttering on a grate due to a low flame, while the title object of this poem “performs its secret ministry / Unhelped by any wind.” For 10 points, name this nocturnal poem by Samuel Taylor Coleridge.", "round" : "2011-ACFNationals-BrownFinal.doc", "seen" : 21, "tournament" : "ACF Nationals", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f798b3d831d6a003588" }, "answer" : "{writing system} [{also} accept {orthography}; accept {alphabet because} of the {Korean} clue]", "category" : "Social Science", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 47.49686509463936, "num" : 18, "question" : "Nüshu is one of these constructs that was used secretly among women in Hunan, China for centuries. The Arabic one was famously defective in its early years, which prompted the dot reform during the Islamic period. Traditionally, Sejong the Great is said to have created the Korean one of these and published it in the Hunminjeongeum in 1446. An example of the abugida variety is Ge'ez, although it existed as an abjad before Christianization circa 350. Consisting of graphemes, most modern ones trace their lineage back to Proto-Canaanite, which was itself derived from Hieratic. Including phonetic varities such as Devanagari as well as logographic varieties such as kanji, alphabets are a type of, for 10 points, this general term for a method of recording language graphically. ", "round" : "Columbia A + Michigan A.doc", "seen" : 30, "tournament" : "Penn Bowl", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ec98b3d831d6a000c39" }, "answer" : "{Catherine II} of Russia [or {Catherine} the {Great}; or {Yekaterina Alekseyevna}; or {Yekaterina}", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : -1, "inc_random" : 344.0525137798395, "num" : 10, "question" : "This ruler was in power during an uprising in the Kazan region known as Pugachev’s Rebellion. This ruler led the coup against Peter III and was in power during all three partitions of Poland. One advisor to this ruler supposedly ordered the construction of fake villages to impress her during a national tour. This ruler was advised by Grigory Potemkin and embraced the writings of such men as Denis Diderot and Voltaire. For 10 points, name this enlightened empress of Russia.", "round" : "districts-01.pdf", "seen" : 230, "tournament" : "HSAPQ VHSL Districts", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e40028b3d831d6a00559e" }, "answer" : "{Mongolia} [or {Mongol Uls}]", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 343.6466231644154, "num" : 14, "question" : "Eighty percent of this country's population took a surname meaning \"master of the blue wolf\" after last names were re-legalized here in 1995. Following this country's 1924 proclamation of a Communist state, its capital received a new name meaning \"Red Hero.\" The desolate areas of this country's west and south are dominated by the (*) Altai Mountains and the Gobi Desert. For 10 points, name this Asian country found south of Russia and north of China, which was the home of conquering horsemen in the late Middle Ages.", "round" : "tourn11-10.pdf", "seen" : 230, "tournament" : "HSAPQ Tournament 11", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e407d8b3d831d6a0072ae" }, "answer" : "Sacramento", "category" : "Geography", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 594.9759955729824, "num" : 19, "question" : "The subrange of the Rockies by this name includes the Guadalupe and Sierra Blanca Peaks. The river of this name receives the McCloud and Feather and flows from the Klamath Mountains to join with the San Joaquin near Suisun Bay. The city of this name has such suburbs as Citrus Heights and Roseville and is thirty miles southwest of Folsom Lake. For 10 points, name this city, home to historical exhibits about the discovery of gold forty-five miles away at Sutter's Mill, and to a governor's mansion that no governor since Ronald Reagan has actually lived in.", "round" : "Round 8.doc", "seen" : 399, "tournament" : "PACE NSC", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2008 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3edf8b3d831d6a001165" }, "answer" : "clouds", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : -1, "inc_random" : 395.4977455283515, "num" : 3, "question" : "One rare type of these formations can be understood as solitons and are known as the \"Morning Glory\" type of them. The bases of these formations are home to \"tags\" or \"scuds,\" which are considered the \"fractus\" type of these entities. One type of these formations are informally known as \"mare's tails.\" Contrails are artificial versions of these formations, which may be \"seeded\" using silver iodide. For 10 points, name these formations that come in cirrus, cumulus, and nimbus types.", "round" : "31.pdf", "seen" : 267, "tournament" : "HSAPQ VHSL Regular Season", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ea28b3d831d6a000339" }, "answer" : "{Inspector Javert} [or {Monsieur Javert}]", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 46.22473486023955, "num" : 19, "question" : "Early in the work this character appears in, he is described as a “dog son of a wolf” that has been given a human face. In a later episode, this character gives another major character a pair of small pistols called fisticuffs to help thwart a robbery. This opponent of the Patron-Minettes was once called to testify against a beggar who'd stolen a bough of apples, while later he is tied to a pole in a restaurant after being discovered by a street urchin carrying an unloaded gun. Later, this character’s life is saved when his nemesis talks Enjolras out of executing him. He allows his enemy to take the critically wounded Marius to his home before abandoning that enemy and throwing himself into the river Seine. For 10 points, name this unforgiving lawman who doggedly pursues Jean Valjean, a noble antagonist in Victor Hugo’s Les Miserables.", "round" : "ACF Regionals 2011 - VCU final.doc", "seen" : 30, "tournament" : "ACF Regionals", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3fa38b3d831d6a003f68" }, "answer" : "{Carmina Burana}", "category" : "Fine Arts", "difficulty" : "Open", "inc_random" : 36.21282511507161, "num" : 5, "question" : "A four-measure movement in this piece consists entirely of whole notes in parts other than the solo soprano, who sings a long series of descending triplets and rising eighth notes while singing “Dulcissime, totam tibi subdo me!” The final movement is in 3/2 time but contains a rest-quarter-quarter-quarter rhythm repeated for the entirety of its middle section. Another movement includes a song sung by a (*) swan while it roasts on a spit, part of a section set “In the Tavern.” Other movements include “Veni, veni, venias” and “In truitina,” both set “In the court of love.” It is most famous for a movement which compares the titular substance is ever waxing and waning like the moon. For 10 points, name this cantata whose most famous for its opening and closing “O Fortuna” movements, based on songs found in Benediktbeuern and composed by Carl Orff.", "round" : "Round 6.doc", "seen" : 24, "tournament" : "VCU Open (Sunday)", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f8f8b3d831d6a003b08" }, "answer" : "{Kenan Thompson} [accept either name]", "category" : "Trash", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 120.4074527935591, "num" : 11, "question" : "On the short-lived cartoon Sit Down, Shut Up, this actor played the principal, Sue Sezno. In Nike's Most Valuable Puppets campaign, he voiced LeBron James. Some of the roles this man has played include McIntosh, a convict who tries to scare prisoners straight, the French Def Comedy Jam star Jean K. Jean, and Deandre Cole, the host of the BET show “What Up With That?” He uses his PlayStation skills to successfully land the plane in the movie Snakes on a Plane. This actor played the titular role in the film version of Fat Albert. For 10 points, name this Saturday Night Live cast member who was previously the comedic partner of Kel Mitchell.", "round" : "USF + Editors 6 - T Party 2010.doc", "seen" : 79, "tournament" : "T-Party", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f6b8b3d831d6a003213" }, "answer" : "{Daniel Boone}", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 343.3251065316144, "num" : 19, "question" : "This person issued a warning before the Battle of Blue Licks which was not heeded, but his later warnings about Dequindre and Black Fish led to a successful defense. This person's life was saved by Simon Kenton after a Shawnee bullet destroyed his knee, and he was later captured by the Shawnee. An employee of Richard Henderson, he worked for the Transylvania Company on the Wilderness Road. Name this man who led the expedition that widened the Cumberland Gap and after whom the first incorporated town in Kentucky was named.", "round" : "03.pdf", "seen" : 227, "tournament" : "NTSS", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ee58b3d831d6a0012e1" }, "answer" : "First Battle of the {Marne} [accept {Battle} of the {Marne} after “a {later battle}”]", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 55.74019591673277, "num" : 10, "question" : "This battle came shortly after the battle of St. Quentin, which ended the career of Charles Lanrezac, prompting the promotion of Louis Franchet d’Esperey. This battle occurred after the Frontiers series of skirmishes. Joseph Joffre kept Joseph Gallieni away from the front, although the latter was praised for his handling of reserve forces. The key moment in this battle came when reserves arrived in taxi cabs from Paris, prompting a surge which caused Helmuth von Moltke’s forces to retreat and abandon the Schlieffen Plan. A later battle at this same site saw Erich Ludendorff’s forces defeated by Ferdinand Foch during the 1918 Spring Offensive. For 10 points, name this 1914 World War I battle, which halted the German offense on Paris and began the trench warfare phase.", "round" : "Packet 1 - finalized (updated).doc", "seen" : 39, "tournament" : "MUT", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3eee8b3d831d6a0014dd" }, "answer" : "{Newt Gingrich} [or {Newton Leroy Gingrich}; or {Newton Leroy McPherson}]", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 344.0453825870063, "num" : 23, "question" : "The foundation that funded this man's \"Renewing American Civilization\" course at two Georgia\n colleges was cleared of wrong-doing by the IRS in 1999. He has been criticized for attacking as \"right-wing\n social engineering\" Paul Ryan's plan to reform Medicare, as well as for divorcing his former high school\n geometry teacher while she was hospitalized for cancer. This politician, who lost his most prominent job in\n November 1998, had pushed for the Contract with America after the election of 1994. For 10 points, name\n this Republican candidate for the Presidency in 2012, who served as a prominent Speaker of the House\n beginning in 1995.", "round" : "12.pdf", "seen" : 224, "tournament" : "NASAT", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e400f8b3d831d6a0058bb" }, "answer" : "{Raymond Chandler}", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 359.9033648034092, "num" : 27, "question" : "In one work by this man, Lew Petrolle runs a bar across the street from the Berglund Apartments, the home of John Dalmas, while another of his works opens with the line “Fiction in any form has always intended to be realistic” and criticizes A.A. Milne's The Red House Mystery. In addition to “Red Wind” and “The Simple Art of [?] Murder”, he focused on a search for Betty Mayfield in the town of Esmeralda in his last completed novel, Playback. That work saw the return of Linda Loring, who had last appeared in a work by this man that saw the death of Terry Lennox, The Long Goodbye. A character this man introduced in “Killer in the Rain” later discovers that Carmen Sternwood killed “Rusty” Regan in another of his works. For 10 points, identify this author whose novels Farewell, My Lovely and The Big Sleep feature his hardboiled private eye Philip Marlowe.", "round" : "FINALS.doc", "seen" : 239, "tournament" : "Mahfouz Memorial Lit", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3fde8b3d831d6a004d0e" }, "answer" : "{Golden} Law [or {Lei Aurea}]", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 56.16697694803588, "num" : 18, "question" : "[MB] One predecessor to this document resulted in the Smash the Kilos Riot, where citizens feared the application of the metric system would result in higher taxes.  The Military Club wrote an influential letter to the crown in support of this, although it is currently overshadowed by celebrations of Zumbi throwing himself off a cliff.  As a consequence of it, the Society for the Promition of Immigration was formed and it also gave rise to the so-called \"People of May 13th\".  Before this document was signed, an act named for Sexagenarians was approved by a Senate led by Baron Cotegipe.  Preceded by the Sariva-Cotegipe Law and the Law of the ? Free Womb--the latter of which was also known as the Rio Branco Law and which granted liberties to children over the age of 21--it was signed by Isabel I while serving as regent for her father, still in Europe.  For 10 points, name this legislation that freed the Brazilian slaves.", "round" : "Packet 4.doc", "seen" : 38, "tournament" : "Gaddis II", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3fee8b3d831d6a0050d0" }, "answer" : "{Daniel Boone}", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 343.7580608390272, "num" : 2, "question" : "This man returned to North Carolina from the French and Indian War in 1756 and married Rebecca Bryan, with whom he had ten children. This man was placed in charge of laying out a road from present-day Kingsport, Tennessee, through the Cumberland Gap and onto the Kentucky River, where this man later resettled with his family in a town he named after himself. For 10 points, name this iconic American explorer and woodsman whose adventures made him one of the first U.S. folk heroes.", "round" : "4q2-03.pdf", "seen" : 231, "tournament" : "HSAPQ 4Q2", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ed98b3d831d6a001024" }, "answer" : "{Ayn Rand} [or {Alisa Zinovyevna Rosenbaum}]", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : -1, "inc_random" : 359.6309364484623, "num" : 10, "question" : "This author wrote a courtroom drama about a man who falls to his death from the Faulkner Building; that play, in which the audience votes as the jury, is The Night of January 16th. She also described a man who writes a textbook with no names in it, Ellsworth Toohey, and conspires with the mediocre Peter Keating to undermine a groundbreaking architect, Howard Roark. For 10 points, identify this author who expounded her Objectivist philosophy in such novels as The Fountainhead and Atlas Shrugged.", "round" : "21.pdf", "seen" : 238, "tournament" : "HSAPQ VHSL Regular Season", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ec78b3d831d6a000bc8" }, "answer" : "{South Africa}", "category" : "Geography", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 594.165338615654, "num" : 8, "question" : "This nation contains the once nominally independent Bantustans of Transkei, Venda, Ciskei, and Bophuthatswana. This nation’s currency is the Rand, and its largest city lies in Gauteng province. Cape Agulhas is the southernmost point in this nation. The (*) Orange river defines part of its border with Namibia. Two of its capitals are Pretoria and Bloemfontein. For 10 points, name this country whose largest cities are Cape Town and Johannesburg, which hosted the 2010 World Cup.", "round" : "tournament17-11.pdf", "seen" : 401, "tournament" : "HSAPQ Tournament 17", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ebf8b3d831d6a0009d8" }, "answer" : "{Che Guevera} [or {Ernesto Guevara} de la {Serna}]", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 343.8325624696445, "num" : 12, "question" : "This man told his killer \"Shoot, coward! You are only going to kill a man\" after he was hunted down in Bolivia. He is the subject of Alberto Korda’s photograph \"Guerrillero Heroico.\" This man was appointed president of the national bank despite receiving training as a (*) doctor. This man attempted to raise a Marxist revolution in the DR Congo and wrote a popular guidebook to guerilla warfare. In his youth, he took a motorcycle journey across South America. For 10 points, name this Cuban revolutionary and advisor to Fidel Castro.", "round" : "04.pdf", "seen" : 227, "tournament" : "HSAPQ Tournament 16", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ed98b3d831d6a000fff" }, "answer" : "{ABO} blood {groups} [or blood {types}]", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 395.2163729597814, "num" : 34, "question" : "A 2007 study found that a bacterial glycosidase could remove the surface antigens used in this classification scheme. This classification scheme is often appended with a plus or minus indicating the presence or absence of a protein first discovered in the rhesus monkey. This classification scheme was invented by Karl Landsteiner, who explained why some blood transfusions failed. For 10 points, name this classification scheme in which a person is classified as A, B, AB, or O.", "round" : "19.pdf", "seen" : 265, "tournament" : "HSAPQ VHSL Regular Season", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ecc8b3d831d6a000ce0" }, "answer" : "\"The {Rime} of the {Ancient Mariner}\"", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : -1, "inc_random" : 359.9184120274149, "num" : 7, "question" : "The speaker of this poem meets a hermit who asks \"What manner of man art thou?\" The revised version of this poem featured the addition of an explanatory gloss. In this poem, the Wedding Guest is accosted and cries \"unhand me, gray-beard loon!\" but is held transfixed by a \"glittering eye\" and hears a tale which features \"water, water everywhere nor any drop to drink.\" For 10 points, an old sailor brings misfortune upon his ship by shooting an albatross in what poem by Samuel Taylor Coleridge?", "round" : "districts-06.pdf", "seen" : 238, "tournament" : "HSAPQ VHSL Districts", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3fb98b3d831d6a0044bb" }, "answer" : "{Constantin Brancusi}", "category" : "Fine Arts", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 422.6983401586767, "num" : 10, "question" : "One of his works is believed to have represented a flying witch in folk tales in his The Sorceress, while his King of Kings was meant to have been displayed in his Temple of Meditation. He depicted a couple intertwined in his The Kiss as well a work which showed the neck and head of the titular royal. Other works include a tall monument made of rhombus shaped pieces located in the town of Targu Jui as well as an oval shaped figure lying on its side of a person asleep. In addition to The Princess X, Endless Column, and Sleeping Muse, this man created a work taxed by U.S. customs that is meant to display the essence of flight.  FTP, identify this Romanian sculptor of Bird in Space. ", "round" : "Round 6.doc", "seen" : 279, "tournament" : "BATE", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f148b3d831d6a001d9e" }, "answer" : "Epimetheus", "category" : "Mythology", "difficulty" : "Open", "inc_random" : 99.60615879972465, "num" : 17, "question" : "One individual commonly cited as a daughter of this figure was the spirit of Excuse, Prophasis, while a Corinthian nymph who was either the daughter or wife of this figure was Ephyra. This figure's daughter was the mother of Protogeneia, Thyia, and the king Hellen, and that daughter previously consulted the oracle at Themis with her husband, the last Bronze Age man, about how to repopulate the human race. This figure's agreement with his brother that the latter would inspect this figure's handiwork eventually resulted in that brother's theft of a fennel-stalk from heaven. That theft led to the creation of this son of Iapetus's wife, who would later bear him Pyrrha; he eventually accepted that clay wife from Hermes despite being warned not to by Zeus. For 10 points, name this creator of animals in Greek mythology and husband of Pandora, the foolish brother of Prometheus.", "round" : "Carleton UCLA - Final.docx", "seen" : 66, "tournament" : "ACF Nationals", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f3e8b3d831d6a002761" }, "answer" : "Strait of {Magellan} [accept {plural}]", "category" : "Geography", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 102.1626634080894, "num" : 10, "question" : "The Evangelistas Lighthouse directly overlooks this body of water, and the Otway Sound is home to a species of penguin named for this body, which connects that sound to the Pacific Ocean. It is bordered to the north by the Brunswick Peninsula, which is home to Cape Froward. Running by the cities of Puerto Saro and Punta Arenas, this body of water serves as an alternate route to the Drake Passage, which itself lies between Cape Horn and Antarctica. It was first discovered in 1520 by its namesake who traveled through this region north of the Tierra del Fuego. For 10 points name this waterway at the southern tip of South America, a certain strait named for a Portuguese explorer.", "round" : "DB 2010 round 6.doc", "seen" : 68, "tournament" : "Delta Burke", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e406b8b3d831d6a006ead" }, "answer" : "the {head} of {Medusa} [do not accept or prompt on “{Medusa}”]", "category" : "Mythology", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : -1, "inc_random" : 683.0689059398137, "num" : 21, "question" : "Drippings from this object were said to have created the Red Sea's coral and Egypt's vipers. This object was used by one hero to wreak havoc on a party on Sephiros, where it killed Polydectes and his nobles. It was also used to ease Atlas's pains, and was often stored in Hermes's magic bag. For 10 points, name this object that was lopped off of a Gorgon's body, has snakes for hair, and will still turn viewers to stone.", "round" : "Round_14_HSAPQ_NSC1.pdf", "seen" : 448, "tournament" : "HSAPQ NSC 1", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2008 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f408b3d831d6a0027e0" }, "answer" : "Italy", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 45.81256136647426, "num" : 7, "question" : "One author from this country wrote Travels with Hyperreality and analyzed luck and Eugene Sue's The Mysteries of Paris in his Serendipities. Another author from this country wrote a work whose chapters are titled after the periodic table, and he analyzed the psychology of Nazi camps in The Drowned and the Saved. Plays from this country include one where the Maniac tricks the police into re-enacting the Accidental Death of an Anarchist, and one where the title figures interrupt a rehearsal. This country is also home to the author of a work starring the Reader, If on a Winter's Night a Traveler, as well as Six Characters in Search of an Author. For 10 points, name this country, home to Italo Calvino and Luigi Pirandello.", "round" : "Round 04 updated.doc", "seen" : 30, "tournament" : "EFT", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ec38b3d831d6a000ace" }, "answer" : "malaria", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 394.9357256325893, "num" : 5, "question" : "Charles Laveran won a Nobel in Medicine for identifying the cause of this disease. One medicine against this disease is called artemisinin. There are seven simian-infecting and five human-infecting species of the causative agent of this disease, with the falciparum variety accounting for most of the mortality. Resistance to this disease caused by (*) Plasmodium is possessed by patients of sickle-cell anemia. This disease can be treated by chewing on cinchona bark, which contains quinine. For 10 points, identify this disease spread by mosquitoes.", "round" : "15.pdf", "seen" : 263, "tournament" : "HSAPQ Tournament 16", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3fcc8b3d831d6a004919" }, "answer" : "{Buddhism} [accept {Theravada Buddhism} or word forms {thereof} before {branch}]", "category" : "Religion", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : -1, "inc_random" : 392.415405649459, "num" : 21, "question" : "The Pali Canon is the standard collection of scriptures of one branch of this religion, which also preaches the samsara, the antithesis of heaven. The sangha, or community, is one of the Three Jewels of this religion, and this religion also preaches the ideas of the Middle Way and the concepts of dukkha and bohdi, both part of the Four Nobel Truths, and the Dharmachakra represents this religion's Eight Fold Path. Theravada and Mahayana are two of the branches of – for 10 points – what Asian religion that preaches the attainment of nirvana, founded by Siddhartha Gautama?", "round" : "FKT Editor 1.rtf", "seen" : 257, "tournament" : "Fall Kickoff Tournament", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f558b3d831d6a002cf5" }, "answer" : "“On First {Looking} into {Chapman's Homer}”", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 45.57118791830726, "num" : 11, "question" : "As noted by Charles Cowden Clarke, this poem was inspired by a passage containing the line “the sea had soakt his heart through.” This poem's speaker tells of having often been told of “one wide expanse” which a certain author “ruled as his demesne,” despite never having “breathe[d] its pure serene.” The speaker also notes that he has been “round many western islands” and travelled much “in the realms of gold.” After performing the titular action, the speaker “felt like some watcher of the skies when a new planet swims into his ken.” He also compares himself to “stout Cortez” staring at the Pacific. For 10 points, name this John Keats poem about the discovery of a certain translation of the work of the author of the Odyssey.", "round" : "Packet 02.doc", "seen" : 29, "tournament" : "MELD", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e408c8b3d831d6a007631" }, "answer" : "{Rhizobium} or {Rhizobia}", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 66.17716798349284, "num" : 16, "question" : "They contain large Sym plasmids that bear nod genes coding for factors that induce cortical cell division, and their gene expression is modified by uptake of flavonoids.  Following the recognition and attachment steps mediated by the protein rhicadhesin, they multiply in infection threads.  Effective strains produce large structures whose reddish color comes from the oxygen buffer leghemoglobin, which is partially encoded in the host plant.  FTP name these gram-negative bacteria that form symbiotic relationships with legumes, producing nitrogen-fixing root nodules.", "round" : "2007 ACF Regionals - Princeton A UIUC B Midwest.doc", "seen" : 42, "tournament" : "ACF Regionals", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2007 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3fc78b3d831d6a0047f9" }, "answer" : "{Jesus} the {Christ} of {Nazareth} [accept {both Jesus} or {Christ}; or of {Galilee}]", "category" : "Religion", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 392.8149924520403, "num" : 6, "question" : "Scholar Ahmad Deedat advanced in his writings the swoon hypothesis regarding this figure. Scholarly investigations of this figure were first initiated by Hermann Samuel Reimarus. This figure was created as a character out of cloth according to Bruno Bauer. This figure's sayings were collected in Greek in the Q document. One of this figure's brothers was the first bishop of Jerusalem known as James the Just. Caiaphas arrested this man while this man was praying on the Mount of Olives. Executed by Pontius Pilate and betrayed by Judas Iscariot, for 10 points, name this son of Mary who founded a namesake religion related to Islam and Judaism.", "round" : "DAFT 2009 Round 01 - Edited - Proofread.doc", "seen" : 260, "tournament" : "DAFT", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ecb8b3d831d6a000cad" }, "answer" : "Jose Albert {Pujols} Alcantara [or {Jose Albert Pujols Alcantara} ]", "category" : "Trash", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : 1, "inc_random" : 848.3319073827006, "num" : 24, "question" : "This player’s home run put his team ahead in game one of the 2006 World Series, a series his team won. This baseball player owns the record for the most 30-home run seasons to begin a player’s career, with ten. For 10 points, name this baseball player, a three-time NL MVP and first baseman for the St. Louis Cardinals.", "round" : "districts-04.pdf", "seen" : 560, "tournament" : "HSAPQ VHSL Districts", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f338b3d831d6a0024b6" }, "answer" : "{Jean-Baptiste Carpeaux}", "category" : "Fine Arts", "difficulty" : "Open", "inc_random" : 35.41359561984427, "num" : 9, "question" : "One of his sculptures depicts a woman on a tree stump as she buries her head into her left knee. In addition to Eve After the Fall and Hector and Astyanax, he created busts for the Marquise de la Valette and the cousin of Napoleon III, Princess Mathilde. His works depicting children include ones in which a nude girl and a nude boy put shells to their ears; those works are Girl With Shell and Neapolitan Fisherboy. His best-known work, however, was created for the (*) Opera Garnier and depicts wings behind a nude group holding hands and frolicking in a circle. At the center of the circle is a male who raises a tambourine. For 10 points, identify French sculptor of La Danse.", "round" : "Lully 12.doc", "seen" : 24, "tournament" : "Chicago Open Arts", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ead8b3d831d6a0005ae" }, "answer" : "{Johann Sebastian Bach}", "category" : "Fine Arts", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : 1, "inc_random" : 422.4587635004427, "num" : 21, "question" : "One of this composer’s works intersperses the words of the gospel with the lyrics of Picander, including the aria “Eli, Eli, lama sabachthani.” This composer wrote six suites for unaccompanied cello in addition to the St. Matthew Passion. He wrote six concertos as a job application for Margrave Christian Ludwig. The composer of the Brandenburg Concertos, this man wrote a prelude and fugue in every major and minor key in another work. For 10 points, name this Baroque composer of The Well-Tempered Clavier.", "round" : "colonia-02.pdf", "seen" : 279, "tournament" : "HSAPQ Colonia 2", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f678b3d831d6a00311c" }, "answer" : "{bears}", "category" : "Mythology", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : 1, "inc_random" : 682.4446358394343, "num" : 17, "question" : "In one myth system, these animals were treated well for one year and eaten, causing them to be transported to the realm of Kim-un Kamui. After becoming a human by praying for 100 days, one of them mated with Hwanung to birth the first Korean emperor. Another encouraged Hanuman to fly across the ocean to find Sita in the Ramayana. In addition to Jambavantha and the one whose sinews were used to make Gleipnir, one was placed on an altar during a feast held by Lycaon before trying to kill his mother, a nymph of Artemis who became one after being seduced by Zeus. For 10 points, name this animal represented by Callisto, who was made into Ursa Major.", "round" : "2.pdf", "seen" : 451, "tournament" : "NASAT", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f5c8b3d831d6a002e5b" }, "answer" : "{North} by {Northwest}", "category" : "Trash", "difficulty" : "Open", "fixed" : -1, "inc_random" : 125.4158534572925, "num" : 6, "question" : "Near the end of this film, the protagonist wryly comments that his two ex-wives divorced him because they said he lived too dull a life. That protagonist has the middle initial “O,” which stands for nothing. In another scene, a character's mother asks two assassins if they are really trying to kill her son. The villain of this film is served by the effeminate Leonard and is named Phillip Vandamm. An early plot element in this film is that the protagonist is mistaken for federal agent (*) George Kaplan, who does not actually exist. The protagonist, advertising executive Roger Thornhill, is framed for the murder of a United Nations delegate. Memorable scenes in this film include Thornhill being shot at by villains in a crop duster and a final chase on the top of Mount Rushmore. For 10 points, name this 1959 Alfred Hitchcock thriller with a directional title.", "round" : "Round 10 - Editors 1.doc", "seen" : 85, "tournament" : "Minnesota Open", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e405c8b3d831d6a006afc" }, "answer" : "{primality} [or {prime}]", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 394.4171115693171, "num" : 23, "question" : "This property is possessed by the constant described in Mills' theorem, and a one way of determining this property is by the Lucas-Lehmer test. A statement about the asymptotic incidence of this property is this property's namesake theorem, and the fact that every number can be written as the sum of two numbers with this property is given as Goldbach's conjecture. Famously subject of a proof by Euclid showing that there are infinitely many numbers with this property, numbers that do not have this property are called composite. For 10 points, name this property of a number that means it is divisible only by one and itself.", "round" : "05.pdf", "seen" : 264, "tournament" : "HSAPQ VHSL States", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3edc8b3d831d6a0010d5" }, "answer" : "entropy", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 395.2424221721012, "num" : 22, "question" : "This property is the only one responsible for the direction of time's arrow. The change in this quantity multiplied by temperature and subtracted from the change in enthalpy gives Gibb's free energy. This property is measured in joules per Kelvin. The value of this quantity will either remain the same or increase according to the Second Law of Thermodynamics. For 10 points, name this measure that can never decrease in a closed system, and which is a measure of the amount of disorder in a system.", "round" : "26.pdf", "seen" : 259, "tournament" : "HSAPQ VHSL Regular Season", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f138b3d831d6a001d65" }, "answer" : "{Monsters}, {Inc.}", "category" : "Trash", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 120.235201621661, "num" : 12, "question" : "One figure in this film takes his girlfriend Celia out to a Japanese restaurant until his friend storms in and causes a scare. The main characters in this film get banished to the Himalayas, where they stay with the Yeti, voiced by John Ratzenberger. One protagonist replaces Henry J. Waternoose as CEO at its end after turning the tables on Randall, his second-best coworker. At the end of this film, the protagonists find out that laughs are more potent than screams after some time with the young girl Boo. For 10 points, name this Pixar movie in which Sulley and the one-eyed Mike are among the title creatures who harness energy by popping out of closets and scaring kids.", "round" : "Yale A.doc", "seen" : 80, "tournament" : "ACF Fall", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3fb18b3d831d6a0042c8" }, "answer" : "The {Posthumous Memoirs} of {Bras Cubas} [or {Epitaph} of a {Small Winner}; or The {Posthumous Memories} of {Brás Cubas}; or {Memórias póstumas} de {Bras Cubas}]", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "Open", "inc_random" : 31.50217964476906, "num" : 1, "question" : "The protagonist of this work imagines inventing an anti-hypochondriacal poultice so that his name can be printed on medicine boxes, and later he regrets killing a black butterfly with a towel. While going to have his watch repaired, the protagonist meets his former lover Marcella. After establishing a trust fund for his lover's maid, the main character loses his chance at a political career when his fiancée marries Lobo Neves instead. After the death of his illegitimate child by Virgilia, the title character is shocked by a new watch that he receives in the mail from his old schoolmate Quincas Borba. Dedicated to “the first worm that gnawed on the cold flesh of my corpse,” for 10 points, name this novel by Joachim Maria Machado de Assis.", "round" : "r17- Editors 3.doc", "seen" : 20, "tournament" : "ACF Nationals", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e406e8b3d831d6a006f69" }, "answer" : "{Avogadro's} constant [prompt on {mole} before mentioned]", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : -1, "inc_random" : 395.3024286355357, "num" : 23, "question" : "The Stark-Einstein photochemical equivalence law uses this value to relate mass to the quanta of radiation it absorbs. The first attempt to calculate this value resulted in the similar Loschmidt constant, and it is multiplied by the elementary charge to produce the Faraday constant. The Boltzmann constant is a ratio of the universal gas constant to this other value, and inverting this number yields the atomic mass unit. For 10 points, name this number that represents the number of atoms or molecules present in a mole of a substance.", "round" : "Round_07_HSAPQ_NSC2.pdf", "seen" : 261, "tournament" : "HSAPQ NSC 2", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2008 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f0a8b3d831d6a001b79" }, "answer" : "{Seventh} Day {Adventists} (prompt on “{Millerites}”, do not prompt on “{Adventist}”)", "category" : "Religion", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 48.68527158419602, "num" : 5, "question" : "This group had its origins in Hiram Edson’s interpretation of a certain religious text, and Ellet Waggoner and Alonzo Jones challenged this group’s belief in sola scriptura, holding instead that salvation came from grace. The visions of Ellen Harmon were used by James White to organize this religious group, and those visions were also believed to have validated this denomination’s sanctuary, shut-door, and (*) “sabbattarian” doctines. This denomination’s founder used the Book of Daniel to predict that 2300 years after Artaxerxes ordered the rebuilding of Jerusalem, a “second awakening,” would occur; the failure of this to take place was known as this denomination’s “great disappointment.” For ten points, identify this Christian denomination founded based on the teachings of William Miller, whose name suggests the unique day on which they observe the Sabbath.", "round" : "FINAL_Laferbrook.doc", "seen" : 34, "tournament" : "Terrapin Invitational", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3fa08b3d831d6a003ebc" }, "answer" : "{Eugene Delacroix} ({del-uh-CWAH}) [or {Ferdinand Victor Eugene Delacroix}]", "category" : "Fine Arts", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 422.0134124907199, "num" : 13, "question" : "This painter depicted treasures lining the floor and soldiers stabbing writhing concubines as a monarch in white and gold reclines on a bed in his The Death of Sardanapalus. This artist also executed a work that includes dead revolutionaries on the ground and a boy waving two (*) pistols. Central to that painting is a bare-breasted woman who holds a musket in one hand and the tricolored French flag in the other. For 10 points, name this French painter of Liberty Leading the People.", "round" : "tourn11-01.pdf", "seen" : 283, "tournament" : "HSAPQ Tournament 11", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f848b3d831d6a003825" }, "answer" : "{Czech} language", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 359.7640487870667, "num" : 13, "question" : "A novel in this language told of a railroad worker's attempts to lose his virginity, Closely Watched Trains. One author in this language wrote The Red Commissar, as well as a novel about a zealous army soldier, The Good Soldier Svejk. In another novel in this language, Ludvik Jahn writes \"Optimism is the opiate of people.” That novel shifts between three other narrators, and is titled The Joke. The same author wrote a novel in this language which ends with a car crash killing Teresa and Tomas, The Unbearable Lightness of Being. For 10 points, name this native language of authors Jaroslav Hašek and Milan Kundera.", "round" : "Round 06.doc", "seen" : 246, "tournament" : "Prison Bowl", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ea48b3d831d6a0003bc" }, "answer" : "{Anglo-Zanzibar} War", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "Open", "fixed" : 1, "inc_random" : 41.65745583232491, "num" : 5, "question" : "At the end of this conflict, the German ship Seeadler rescued the losing side’s commander. One party to this conflict had to deal with the questionable loyalty of askari troops under Arthur Raikes. That side's land forces were commanded by Lloyd Mathews, while Admiral Harry Rawson held a blockade with the ships Racoon, Thrush, and Sparrow. The initial cause of the war was the death of Hamad bin Thuwaini, which led to a coup by Khalid bin Bargash, who seized the \"House of Wonders\" or Beit al-Ajaib - a palace located in modern-day Stone Town. Khalid escaped thanks to German aid at this conflict, which is often called the shortest war in history. FTP, name this 1896 war which may have lasted about 40 minutes, a conflict between England and a protectorate which later became part of Tanzania.", "round" : "PACKET03Peterson.doc", "seen" : 39, "tournament" : "Chicago Open", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e40138b3d831d6a00597a" }, "answer" : "{Thomas Tallis}", "category" : "Fine Arts", "difficulty" : "Open", "inc_random" : 35.67922424618155, "num" : 15, "question" : "This composer's organ interludes include two Felix namques. He wrote a remarkably long antiphon adhering to the Phrygian mode, unusually for the time period; that work was later made into a 5-part mass of the same name, Salve intemerata. In one of his motets, the two sopranos sing the same line half a bar apart, while four of the other five voices sing the same melody, two inverted, at different tempos. That work, Miserere nostri, was the last of a set of 34 motets created with a younger colleague, the Cantiones sacrae, and that colleague wrote Ye Sacred Muses to commemorate this man's death. He set two Lamentations of Jeremiah to a 5-part male chorus, and composed a 40-person motet, Spem in alium. For 10 points, name this early British composer, one of whose themes was used for a fantasia by Ralph Vaughan Williams.", "round" : "KLEE - Round 1.doc", "seen" : 24, "tournament" : "Minnesota Open KLEE Fine Arts", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f218b3d831d6a002075" }, "answer" : "{DeWitt Clinton}", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 56.17206781636924, "num" : 21, "question" : "This politician was elected Senator over Matthew Clarkson in the first election that required tabulating a joint ballot of the state Assembly and Senate. This man was opposed by the Bucktails, and he was elected governor for the last time with the People's Party. He ran on the Peace Party ticket with Jared Ingersoll in the 1812 election, where he lost to James Madison. As mayor, this man led a commission which proposed a plan later modified by Central Park, the grid layout of most of Manhattan. Gouverneur Morris was the chair of a commission that this man effectively spearheaded to build a structure linking the Great Lakes to New York City. For 10 points, name this longtime mayor of New York City and governor of New York who worked to build the Erie Canal.", "round" : "2010 - ACF Regionals - Brown + VCU + Oklahoma.doc", "seen" : 36, "tournament" : "ACF Regionals", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f3f8b3d831d6a0027a0" }, "answer" : "{Gustav Mahler}", "category" : "Fine Arts", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 59.28714642394334, "num" : 12, "question" : "The scherzo of this man's second symphony is used in Luciano Berio's Sinfonia, and is followed by the movement \"Urlicht.\" This man's last symphony was completed by Deryck Cooke. This man's first symphony contains \"Frere Jacques\" set in a minor key, and quotes his own piece Songs of a Wayfarer. This man's eighth symphony uses text from Faust and the hymn \"Veni, Creator Spiritus,\" and is known as the Symphony of a Thousand. For 10 points, name this Austrian composer whose first symphony is nicknamed the Titan.", "round" : "DB 2010 round 9.doc", "seen" : 40, "tournament" : "Delta Burke", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ebd8b3d831d6a00095c" }, "answer" : "{Russia} [or {Russian Federation}]", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 343.7990717203356, "num" : 3, "question" : "One person from this country married a British citizen named Alex before serving as the alleged CEO of PropertyFinder LLC. Matt Taibbi and Mark Ames founded a widely read English newspaper in this nation called \"The eXile.\" It is the home nation of Cynthia Murphy and Anna Chapman, two members of the so-called \"Illegals Program\" who were arrested in the (*) U.S. and swapped for prisoners in this nation in 2010. For 10 points, name this country whose spies were captured in the U.S. in 2010, and which is nominally led by president Dmitri Medvedev.", "round" : "14.pdf", "seen" : 233, "tournament" : "HSAPQ Tournament 15", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f518b3d831d6a002bf1" }, "answer" : "{Irrawaddy} River", "category" : "Geography", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 103.0628786694724, "num" : 6, "question" : "N'mai and Mali rivers in Kachin Province. At one time this river flowed into the Sittoung and continued on to the Gulf of Martaban, and cities on its banks include Hinhada and Mogok. The first European to sail this river was a Venetian named Nicolo di Conti who was traveling to the city of Ava, and this body of water was the site of the golden barges of its kings. One city on this river was founded by King Mindon and was given a name meaning “Mound of Gems.” This river is often the site of the transport of teak logs, and much of this river's traffic is due to the fact that the nearby Salween River is barely navigable. Emptying into the Andaman sea and passing through the city of Mandalay, for 10 points, identify this river which empties into the sea at Yangon, the principal river of Burma.", "round" : "Round 03.doc", "seen" : 67, "tournament" : "Harvard International", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f828b3d831d6a00379f" }, "answer" : "The {O.C.}", "category" : "Trash", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 120.9091577832587, "num" : 4, "question" : "The final episode of this show saw some of its characters watching Briefcase or No Briefcase and was set some six months after the previous episode. A much earlier episode sees one character receiving a \"Model Home Mix\", and recurring characters have included tennis instructor Spencer Built. Finley Quaye's song \"Dice\" played at a party in Oliver Trask's penthouse in a scene paid homage in creator Josh Schwartz's later show Chuck. When the lead character isn't racing to kiss his girlfriend on New Year's or kissing Mischa Barton, he's engaging in fisticuffs with people like Luke, Volchok, or his brother Trey. For 10 points, name this Fox show about teenagers like Marissa, Summer, and Ryan in the titular California location.", "round" : "UWashA.doc", "seen" : 84, "tournament" : "Princeton Buzzerfest", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ec48b3d831d6a000af8" }, "answer" : "{Sir Friedrich Wilhelm Herschel}", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 395.2005822930951, "num" : 1, "question" : "This scientist was the first to note that Mars's polar caps have seasonal changes, leading this man to propose that they are made of water. He was the first to realize that double stars actually contained two gravitationally bound stars, leading to him coining the term binary star. This man also coined the word asteroid. He discovered Enceladus and Mimas, as well as infrared radiation. This scientist discovered the moon (*) Oberon, as well as the object it orbits. For 10 points, name this discoverer of Uranus.", "round" : "tournament17-02.pdf", "seen" : 265, "tournament" : "HSAPQ Tournament 17", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e40748b3d831d6a0070ad" }, "answer" : "The Garden of {Earthly Delights}", "category" : "Fine Arts", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 422.0209893314168, "num" : 11, "question" : "In one corner of this work, a man offers up an apple to a bird he is balancing on his feet, while in another corner, a woman can be seen holding what looks like an oversized pear. This work also depicts a pair of ears placed together near a fire, and a man is held fast to an overturned table by a dagger pierced through his hand. In another part of this work, an enormous bird feeds a group of humans standing under a branch, and nearby a man is carrying a large mussel shell containing another man. More notably, a man with tree-like arms has a round disk on his head that carries a group of creatures, and Jesus holds the hand of Eve in the Garden of Eden.  For 10 points, name this triptych that depicts scenes from Eden and Hell on the side panels, a creation of Hieronymus Bosch.", "round" : "NNT_Packet_7.doc", "seen" : 283, "tournament" : "NNT", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2008 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3fd08b3d831d6a004a02" }, "answer" : "{conditioning} [accept {operant conditioning} until mentioned]", "category" : "Social Science", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : -1, "inc_random" : 338.2633010195569, "num" : 1, "question" : "One version of this process can lead to psychological extinction when previously-used reinforcements are no longer present and can be studied with Skinner's box. In addition to the operant type, another type was studied in an experiment where food delivery was paired with a ringing bell, which eventually induced salivation on its own. For 10 points, name this central action of behaviorism whose “classical” type was demonstrated by Pavlov's dogs, the association of stimuli with previously unrelated behavior.", "round" : "round06.doc", "seen" : 224, "tournament" : "Fall Novice", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e40668b3d831d6a006d9c" }, "answer" : "{Eero Saarinen}", "category" : "Fine Arts", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 422.5485678389668, "num" : 3, "question" : "Many of this man's works were produced by family friends Hans and Florence Knoll, including one with a white frame and red cushion, the iconic Tulip chair. Collaborating with the president of the Cranbrook Academy of Art, he designed the Kleinhans Music Hall in Buffalo, New York. The roof of another of his buildings has 1/8th of a sphere, and serves as a concert hall in MIT. His other works include the General Motors Technical Center, the TWA flight center in New York, and Dulles International Airport Terminal near Washington, D.C. For 10 points, name this architect who designed the Gateway Arch in St. Louis, Missouri, a man of Finnish descent.", "round" : "Packet 4.doc", "seen" : 276, "tournament" : "Prison Bowl", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e404d8b3d831d6a006786" }, "answer" : "{School} for {Scandal}", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 359.7798336832784, "num" : 10, "question" : "In act four of this play one character holds an auction for all of his family portraits, but refuses to sell the picture of his uncle. In the final act Crabtree and Sir Benjamin Backbite make up a story about a duel, and another character disguises himself as the moneylender Mr. Premium while meeting his relatives. Sir Peter Teazle discovers the affair between Joseph and his wife Lady Teazle, and the play ends with Sir Oliver giving his blessing to the marriage of Charles Surface and Maria. FTP, name this play that features Lady Sneerwell, written by Richard Brinsley Sheridan.", "round" : "HFT Round 09 ADV FINISHED.doc", "seen" : 238, "tournament" : "HFT", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2008 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f458b3d831d6a00292d" }, "answer" : "{shogunates} [accept {bakufu}; prompt “{governments} of {Japan},” “{dynasties} of {Japan},” and the like]", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : -1, "inc_random" : 344.2942287931219, "num" : 3, "question" : "One of these governments was dominated by regents of the Hojo clan. Another sent the diplomat Faxecura to Acapulco and the Vatican, but later banned Christianity prior to the Shimabara rebellion. That one came to power after the Battle of Sekigahara and instituted sakoku, an isolationist policy ended in 1867.  For 10 points, name this form of governance exemplified by the rule of Ieyasu Tokugawa, in which power rested with the namesake Japanese warlord.", "round" : "Packet 1.doc", "seen" : 228, "tournament" : "Fall Novice", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f998b3d831d6a003d25" }, "answer" : "{Auguste Rodin}", "category" : "Fine Arts", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 421.7732848627493, "num" : 16, "question" : "Three identical men standing stooped at different angles appear in this artist's work The Three Shades. This artist depicted Saint Pierre's followers from the title city being led to their execution in one of his works, and he depicted the title writer in a robe in a monument commissioned by the Société des Gens des Lettres. In addition to Monument to Balzac and the Burghers of Calais, more well-known works of this sculptor are Paolo and Francesca performing the title action and a man sitting and pondering, two details from this man's The Gates of Hell. For 10 points, identify this French sculptor of The Kiss and The Thinker.", "round" : "Round 7.doc", "seen" : 280, "tournament" : "TJ NAREN", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e406d8b3d831d6a006f37" }, "answer" : "{Pullman} Strike", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : -1, "inc_random" : 343.0949616015423, "num" : 21, "question" : "Richard Olney claimed that this event brought the nation to \"the ragged edge of anarchy\", and a meeting at Briggs House led by Samuel Gompers cautioned against sympathy action in this event. John Peter Altgeld refused to dispatch state militia to quell this event, and federal action was taken to quell it due to interference with the mail service. Clarence Darrow defended its leaders on contempt charges arising from this event, and it was broken in part due to Grover Cleveland's ordering of 2,500 federal troops to Chicago. For 10 points, name this 1894 strike of railroad workers led by Eugene V. Debs.", "round" : "Round_05_HSAPQ_NSC2.pdf", "seen" : 232, "tournament" : "HSAPQ NSC 2", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2008 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3e9e8b3d831d6a000275" }, "answer" : "“ {Snows} of {Kilimanjaro} ”", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "College", "fixed" : 1, "inc_random" : 45.94174275128171, "num" : 17, "question" : "One character in this story claims death is not “a scythe and a skull” but two policemen on bicycles after recalling a hotel owner in Triberg who hung himself after a bad skiing season. The main character tells a woman “the marvelous thing is that it’s painless” before she tries to make him drink broth instead of whiskey. The protagonist remembers giving Williamson morphine tablets so he can commit suicide before Compton takes him on a plane ride to the top of a mountain. In this story Helen tries to care for her bed-ridden lover who develops a gangrene infection from a scratch on his leg while on a hunting trip in Africa. For 10 points, name this Hemingway short story in which the writer Harry fantasizes on his deathbed.", "round" : "ACF Regionals 2011 - Editors 2 final.doc", "seen" : 30, "tournament" : "ACF Regionals", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f918b3d831d6a003b6f" }, "answer" : "preludes", "category" : "Fine Arts", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 58.7066772126127, "num" : 10, "question" : "Francois Couperin included an allemande and eight of these pieces to explain correct fingering in his book The Art of Playing the Harpsichord. Out of homage to that composer, the first movement of Le Tombeau de Couperin is one of these pieces. When prefaced by the word “chorale,” this is the name of the forty-six pieces in J.S. Bach's Little Organ Book. Rachmaninoff used one of these pieces nicknamed “chord” as the theme for his Variations on a Theme of (*) Chopin. The Opus 28 of Chopin consists of twenty-four of these piano pieces, including one nicknamed “Raindrop.” The Well-Tempered Clavier begins with one of these pieces in C major, and pairs them with fugues. For 10 points, identify these short pieces named because they originally served as introductions to longer works.", "round" : "THUNDER Round 11.docx", "seen" : 35, "tournament" : "THUNDER II", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f018b3d831d6a001946" }, "answer" : "Ubiquitin", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 66.75155549407934, "num" : 7, "question" : "In eukaryotes, the genes that encode this protein are arranged in tandem repeats, and this protein is thought to regulate gene transcription by binding to histone H2A. The attachment of this protein to its target is mediated by a hierarchical three enzyme cascade that starts with an E1 activating protein and ends with a substrate specific E3 ligase. This protein uses a glycine residue to bind to a lysine residue on the target protein and can tag a transmembrane protein for removal from a membrane or bind to cyclin to regulate cell division. Its most well known function occurs when a chain of at least four of these molecules attaches to a target, which directs target proteins to the proteasome. For 10 points, name this abundant protein that is used to target other proteins for degradation.", "round" : "Packet 04.doc", "seen" : 56, "tournament" : "SACK", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3fe88b3d831d6a004f68" }, "answer" : "neutrons", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : -1, "inc_random" : 394.541012122063, "num" : 26, "question" : "Enrico Fermi proposed that an atom's preferred mode of beta decay depends on whether it has too many or too few of these particles, which are often ejected during spontaneous fission. Carbon-14 dating makes use of the decay of one of these particles, which consists of one up and two down quarks. The number of them in the nucleus is equal to the difference between atomic mass and atomic number. For 10 points, name these particles discovered by James Chadwick, which are slightly heavier than protons and electrically neutral.", "round" : "4q1-06.pdf", "seen" : 262, "tournament" : "HSAPQ 4Q1", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3e948b3d831d6a00003a" }, "answer" : "{russalka}", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "Open", "fixed" : 1, "inc_random" : 30.95764910499565, "num" : 8, "question" : "An analogous creature to these beings in another mythos was called the vele, and a story tells of how Prince Marko captured a leader of these beings named Nadanojla by having his falcon steal that leader’s headdress. These creatures were described as either ugly or beautiful depending on whether tales of them came from the north or the south, and they were sometimes subservient to a chief who took the form of a fat, jolly green man. According to one legend, these beings could survive outside their natural environment so long as they kept possession of a comb, and these beings were celebrated during the Radunitsa feast. One story about these beings tells of how a young seal hunter named Ivan Savelyevich encountered one while playing his balalaika and fell in love with her, but eventually left her by crossing himself. Most encounters with these beings would end poorly for the man, as they would typically end up making him dance to death or drowning him. For ten points, identify these analogues of the Ondine and the Lorelei, water sprites of Slavic myth.", "round" : "2011-ACFNationals-ChicagoCUVAMarylandFinal.doc", "seen" : 20, "tournament" : "ACF Nationals", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3fd48b3d831d6a004aef" }, "answer" : "buckminsterfullerene ", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 65.4623054524418, "num" : 21, "question" : "The reversible derivatization of these compounds and separation of their functionalized intermediates is the Bingel-retro strategy. Their crystals can undergo exohedral (*) alkali-metal doping and when they enclose metal atoms they are endohedral. They can form from laser vaporization of graphite rods and often consist of pentagons and hexagons forming cages and planar sheets such as graphene. For 10 points, name this family of carbon allotropes that include nanotubes and buckyballs.", "round" : "04_fichte09.doc", "seen" : 46, "tournament" : "FICHTE", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3fb08b3d831d6a004268" }, "answer" : "{LDL} [or {low-density lipoprotein}; prompt on {cholesterol} until mentioned]", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "Open", "inc_random" : 49.04225192242302, "num" : 23, "question" : "This molecule's receptor, which is degraded by PCSK9, contains three EGF-like domains sandwiched around a beta-propeller domain. The gene for that receptor is activated by the bHLH fragment of SREBP. Endocytosis of this molecule can induce macrophages to become foam cells. ASPs can inhibit a reaction in which copper ions oxidize this molecule; an important step in that reaction is the modification of apoprotein B-100. Ezitimibe is one drug that reduces the amount of this molecule in the body; however, it is much more effective when used with HMG-CoA reductase inhibitors, or statins. For 10 points, name this molecule responsible for depositing cholesterol on artery walls, sometimes referred to as the “bad” cholesterol.", "round" : "r12- Rutgers.doc", "seen" : 34, "tournament" : "ACF Nationals", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f968b3d831d6a003c8e" }, "answer" : "{Daniel Webster}", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 343.0733170728199, "num" : 5, "question" : "This man authored a document defending the American right to be interested in Hungarian affairs, the Hulsemann Letter, and was criticized by Ralph Waldo Emerson following his \"Seventh of March\" speech. He attacked nullification in a speech ending \"Liberty and Union, now and for ever, one and inseparable!\", his Second Reply to Hayne, and this politician helped negotiate a treaty disputing the Maine-New Brunswick border named for him and Ashburton. He represented Dartmouth in Dartmouth College v. Woodward and was Secretary of State under Millard Fillmore. For 10 points, name this Massachusetts Senator and Northern member of the \"Great Triumvirate\".", "round" : "Round 13.doc", "seen" : 226, "tournament" : "TJ NAREN", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3fbd8b3d831d6a004581" }, "answer" : "The {Grouch} [or {Dyskolos}; or The {Bad-Tempered Man} or {pretty much} any equivalents]", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "Open", "inc_random" : 30.69839884024113, "num" : 18, "question" : "This play ends with Getas dragging the sleeping protagonist from his house, pounding on his door, and bombarding him with requests to borrow Persian rugs and a bronze wine-bowl. A comic scene in this play occurs when the cook Sikon drags a sheep onstage and attempts to sacrifice it to the shrine of the Nymphs. After Simiche drops a bucket and a mattock into a well, this play's protagonist falls in after them, causing him to adopt his rescuer, Gorgias, as his son. Beginning with a prologue spoken by Pan, this play is set in Phyle, and ends happily with Sostratos being betrothed to Myrrhine, the daughter of the title character, who first appears wishing he owned the head of Medusa so he could turn everyone else into stone. The only fully extant example of its author's New Comedy, for 10 points, name this play by Menander about the ill-tempered farmer Knemon.", "round" : "Packet 04 - Ragged Dick and the Algerian Heroes.doc", "seen" : 57, "tournament" : "Chicago Open", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3fa68b3d831d6a004025" }, "answer" : "{Herbert Paul Grice} [accept {Relevance} before “{this thinker}”; I guess accept {irony} before “{this thinker}” as {well} since {Sperber} and {Wilson did} a {lot} of {work} on that]", "category" : "Social Science", "difficulty" : "Open", "inc_random" : 38.25675065116957, "num" : 23, "question" : "Dan Sperber and Deirdre Wilson wrote a book named after one of this thinker’s constructions, claiming it subsumed the three similar constructs with which it was grouped. According to this thinker, certain attempts at communication tend to be non-conventional, calculable, non-detachable, and defeasible. This thinker described exploitation of his constructs through flouting them as a form of communication. This man defined a speaker trying to impart something to a hearer merely by having the hearer recognize his intention as non-natural meaning, or meaning-nn. His theory of implicatures espouses that people pay attention to Quality, Quantity, Relevance, and Manner in making cooperative utterances. For 10 points, name this man who did foundational work in pragmatics, including the formulation of his four maxims for conversation.", "round" : "2011-ACFNationals-BrownFinal.doc", "seen" : 25, "tournament" : "ACF Nationals", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3fd08b3d831d6a0049e0" }, "answer" : "Sikhism", "category" : "Religion", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 392.5335790708195, "num" : 2, "question" : "One founding story of this religion tells of five men who went into a tent expecting decapitation, starting this faith's military order, the Khalsa. That term now applies to anyone who undergoes this faith's baptism from an iron bowl of water, and such adherents carry the kirpan, a ceremonial dagger, and maintain long hair as part of the “Five K's.” For 10 points, name this monotheistic religion expounded by Nanak which also counts the Adi Granth among its Gurus, a faith from the Punjab region of India whose male adherents usually wear turbans.", "round" : "round04.doc", "seen" : 259, "tournament" : "Fall Novice", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3eba8b3d831d6a0008c4" }, "answer" : "{Scott Pilgrim} vs. the {World}", "category" : "Trash", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : -1, "inc_random" : 847.6941160713322, "num" : 12, "question" : "One character in this film quickly delivers packages by traveling through subspace. Another character talks about Pac-Man to impress girls. At a battle of the bands, its protagonist defeats the Katayanagi brothers and later gains the “Power of Self-Respect” after telling his ex-girlfriend Knives that he cheated on her. Based on a comic series by Bryan Lee O'Malley, it sees the title character engage in (*) video game battles with seven evil exes in order to date Ramona Flowers. For 10 points, name this 2010 comedy starring Michael Cera.", "round" : "07.pdf", "seen" : 572, "tournament" : "HSAPQ Tournament 15", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ea18b3d831d6a0002fd" }, "answer" : "{Getúlio Dornelles Vargas}", "category" : "History", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 56.41128560784273, "num" : 3, "question" : "His bodyguard Gregório Fortunato was accused of masterminding one assassination plot for this man, which led to him writing the Letter of Testament. He ended the politics of “coffee with milk,” and Eduardo Gomes resigned his position due to his policies. He served in the treasury department for Washington Luis, and came to power after the overthrow of Júlio Prestes. He fabricated the communist “Cohen Plan” and supported a movement founded by Plínio Salgado. He won power in part due to the “tenentes” and was deposed in a coup by Eurico Dutra. After the Rua Tonelero plot to kill his opponent, Carlos Lacerda, in the 1954 presidential election was exposed, he killed himself. For ten points, name this multiple-time president who created the Estado Novo in Brazil.", "round" : "ACF Regionals 2011 - State College and Yale C final.doc", "seen" : 39, "tournament" : "ACF Regionals", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f238b3d831d6a0020db" }, "answer" : "{Pathetique} or Symphony {No.} 6 in {B minor}", "category" : "Fine Arts", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 59.02482340368442, "num" : 18, "question" : "This work's final section begins with the first and second violins successively playing alternating notes of the main theme, and this piece concludes with a muted fanfare of stopped horns and the single stroke of a tam-tam while the music fades into quiet. The \"Allegro con grazia\" second movement is a waltz written in the unusual time signature of 5/4. In this symphony's first movement a theme inspired by Don Jose' \"Flower Song\" from Carmen slowly dwindles until it is played at a volume marked with six Ps. During this work's \"adagio lamentoso\" final movement a triple forte drumroll interrupts the recapitulation of ends the \"desperation\" theme. Premiered nine days before the composer's death from cholera, for 10 points, name this final Tchaikovsky symphony.", "round" : "2010 - ACF Regionals - Editors 3.doc", "seen" : 39, "tournament" : "ACF Regionals", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3e9a8b3d831d6a00019d" }, "answer" : "{Jahn-Teller} effect [or theorem; or distortion]", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "Open", "fixed" : 1, "inc_random" : 50.24538110219873, "num" : 14, "question" : "Recent investigations of this effect have concerned cooperative variants in crystals and its relation to fullerenes and other icosahederal systems. Generating an avoided crossing, the pseudo version occurs in fluxional molecules and manifests in stereochemical non-rigidity of molecules and ions. One way to explain this effect mathematically involves the odd terms in the vibronic perturbation expansion. Experimental demonstration of this phenomenon is observed in UV-VIS absorbance spectra as split bands. Another important property of this theorem is its failure to predict directionality, which explains the shortening of z-axis ligands. The most paradigmatic example is in the form of six-coordinate copper (II ) complexes with three electrons in the two e-sub-g orbitals. For 10 points, name this doubly-eponymous theorem that describes the geometrical distortion of non-linear molecules with degenerate electronic ground states to lower the overall energy and symmetry of the complex.", "round" : "2011-ACFNationals-RiceTorontoUSCFinal.doc", "seen" : 34, "tournament" : "ACF Nationals", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f288b3d831d6a002218" }, "answer" : "pancreas", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 66.52708773571067, "num" : 21, "question" : "The lesser end of this organ extends towards the spleen and is placed over the left kidney. The ascending portion of the transverse meso-colon covers the convex front part of the body of this organ. The splenic artery and vein can be found in the thick upper border of this organ, through which the Canal of Wirsung extends from the left to right of the substance of this organ. Its secretions include chymotrypsin and trypsin, which help break down proteins, and the sphincter of Oddi controls the release of liquids through the Ampulla of Vater, which contains secretions from the gallbladder and this organ. The alpha cells of regions of this organ secrete glucagon, while the beta cells secrete insulin. For 10 points, name this organ, home to the islets of Langerhans.", "round" : "ACF Winter 2010 - Eden Prairie + Maryland B.pdf", "seen" : 45, "tournament" : "ACF Winter", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ea08b3d831d6a0002d3" }, "answer" : "{Erik Alfred Satie}", "category" : "Fine Arts", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 58.71078886603937, "num" : 5, "question" : "One piece by this composer contains instructions like “ask insistently within yourself” and “arm yourself with clairvoyance.” This composer wrote a work that includes a comically bad rendition of Chopin’s Funeral March and ends with a parody of Beethoven’s Eighth Symphony. He instructed a note should be repeated 840 times in his work Vexations. This composer wrote a piece whose first part is about a sea cucumber, while another piece is based on a poem by Contamine about a Greek athletic event and was mistakenly grouped by John Cage as part of his “furniture music.” For 10 points, name this French experimental composer who wrote Desiccated Embryos and three Gymnopedies.", "round" : "ACF Regionals 2011 - RPI A and Minnesota final.doc", "seen" : 37, "tournament" : "ACF Regionals", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f418b3d831d6a002823" }, "answer" : "The {Brothers Karamazov}", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 45.92636900162324, "num" : 8, "question" : "One character in this novel tells a story about a sinner who is pulled from the lake of fire but falls back in because she kicked sinners and shattered her onion. The author of this novel was inspired by a scene from Don Carlos to depict a dialogue with Jesus and the head of the Inquisition at one point in this book. One character in this work's mother is Lizaveta, while its sixth part describes the priest Zosima, who dies around the time Alyosha kisses the earth. Eventually we learn from a confession that Smerdyakov murdered Fyodor, even though the final part of this novel describes Dmitri's trial and his escape from Siberia. For 10 points, name this novel about Dmitri, Ivan and Alexei, a book by Fyodor Dostoyevsky.", "round" : "Round 08 updated.doc", "seen" : 31, "tournament" : "EFT", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e402b8b3d831d6a005f88" }, "answer" : "Joseph {Smith}", "category" : "Religion", "difficulty" : "HS", "fixed" : 1, "inc_random" : 391.7206350611523, "num" : 11, "question" : "This man tried to defend against his death at the hands of a mob with a pepper pistol but was shot in jail. He and his 10,000 followers were forced out of Missouri and into Illinois during a war that saw the death of 22 people in 1838. In 1827, he married Emma Hale, and in 1831 he tried to move his followers to Independence, Missouri. He established the city of Nauvoo in Illinois, which was the site of another war in 1844. This caused his followers to again move, this time to the West, where later they would perpetrate the Mountain Meadows Massacre. For 10 points, name this man who supposedly met Moroni, the first leader of the Church of Latter Day Saints.", "round" : "Packet 3.doc", "seen" : 264, "tournament" : "Prison Bowl", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2009 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ee78b3d831d6a001356" }, "answer" : "{crystals} [accept {crystal lattice} at any point]", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 65.51943001174368, "num" : 14, "question" : "Anomalies in these structures may include ones which obey the conservation of charge that are named for Frenkel and Schottky. Their analysis invokes the reciprocal k-space, which is the Fourier transform of the real space describing them. In one technique used to analyze them, the incident angle that gives the maximum constructive interference is the inverse-sine of the wavelength multiple divided by twice the spacing in them according to Bragg’s law. They are studied using X-ray diffraction. For 10 points, identify these structures whose constituent materials are found in repeating patterns, and whose three-dimensional arrangement is called a “lattice.”", "round" : "Packet 5 - finalized.doc", "seen" : 44, "tournament" : "MUT", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f878b3d831d6a0038f7" }, "answer" : "hydrazine", "category" : "Science", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 65.95148404617794, "num" : 14, "question" : "The use of an ethanolic type of this compound is used at reflux as a part of the Ing-Manske procedure to cleave N-alkylated phthalimide derivatives for use in the Gabriel Synthesis. The original commercial process for producing this involves, in the first steps, the oxidation of ammonia to chloramine with sodium hypochlorite. This compound is involved in the transformation of the carbonyl group of a ketone or aldehyde into a methyl group in the Wolf-Kishner reduction. Under the code name “B-Stoff,” a hydrated version of this compound was used to initiate combustion in the BV 143 during WWII and is used in the APUs of the International Space Station as a monopropellant. Produced in the Olin Raschig process, for 10 points, name this compound with formula N2H4.", "round" : "Round by Editors 1.docx", "seen" : 42, "tournament" : "Sun n Fun", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3ee98b3d831d6a0013a5" }, "answer" : "{William Somerset Maugham}", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 46.5861196576152, "num" : 2, "question" : "One of this non-Henry James author’s protagonists is inspired by such books as Ernest Renan’s Life of Jesus and is advised to seek “the figure in the carpet” by the poetaster Cronshaw. In another of his novels, a bottle of Zubrowka tempts Sophie Macdonald back into alcoholism, while the protagonist uses the hypnotic powers he’d learned in India to cure Gray Maturin, the husband of his ex-fiancée Isabel. The protagonist of his most famous work lives for a time with Norah Nesbit and carries on a tumultuous romance with Mildred Rogers, but is finally able to find peace with Thorpe Athelney’s daughter Sally. For 10 points, identify this author who created Larry Darrell and Philip Carey in The Razor’s Edge and Of Human Bondage, respectively.", "round" : "zFinals 1 - finalized.doc", "seen" : 31, "tournament" : "MUT", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f618b3d831d6a002f81" }, "answer" : "{Paul Gauguin}", "category" : "Fine Arts", "difficulty" : "College", "inc_random" : 59.29358107387088, "num" : 6, "question" : "In one of his paintings a being with bright red hair and cloven hoofs, who is thought to represent Meyer de Haan, looks over two seated women. One painting by this man shows a figure plucking a fruit from a tree at the center while a baby and an old woman are used to illustrate the progression of life, and another work shows pious Breton women who have a vision of the title event. In addition to Jacob Wrestling the Angel and Where do we come from? What are we? Where are we going?, he painted two works depicting the colorful subject of a crucifixion. For 10 points, identify this post-impressionist artist who painted The Green Christ and The Yellow Christ and spent many years in Tahiti.", "round" : "MUT 2010 - Minnesota 3 - Done.doc", "seen" : 37, "tournament" : "MUT", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2010 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3eeb8b3d831d6a001447" }, "answer" : "{Paul Hindemith}", "category" : "Fine Arts", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 421.6730917603709, "num" : 11, "question" : "Kemal Ataturk commissioned this composer to reorganize musical education in Turkey. This composer\n collaborated with Leonid Massine on a ballet about the life of St. Francis, Nobilissima Visione, and with\n George Balanchine on the ballet The Four Temperaments. This proponent of \"Gebrauchsmusik\" paid\n tribute to the Brandenburg Concertos by writing a series of chamber concerti he called \"Kammermusik.\"\n He adapted incidental music from Turandot to compose his Symphonic Variations on Themes by Von\n Weber, and wrote an opera about the life of Matthias Grunewald. For 10 points, name this 20th century\n neo-Classical German composer of Mathis der Mahler.", "round" : "06.pdf", "seen" : 283, "tournament" : "NASAT", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
, { "__v" : 0, "_id" : { "$oid" : "506e3f8e8b3d831d6a003ac4" }, "answer" : "{Kawabata Yasunari} [accept names in either order]", "category" : "Literature", "difficulty" : "HS", "inc_random" : 360.6551443105563, "num" : 12, "question" : "A short story by this author follows a college student's feelings for a performer who turns out to be just a little girl, entitled The Dancing Girl of Izu. One of this writer’s novels describes the relationship between Fumiko Ota, her mother, and the orphan Kikuji, and focuses on a tea ceremony. This man’s journalistic work on Honinbo Shusai's final match led to a novel in which Otake defeats a dying man in the titular [*] game. Shimamura, the protagonist of one this man’s works, falls in love with the geisha Komako, a resident of a hot-spring town in the titular region of Japan. For 10, name this Nobel laureate who wrote Thousand Cranes, The Master of Go, and Snow Country.", "round" : "Finals 1.doc", "seen" : 239, "tournament" : "St. Anselms and Torrey Pines", "type" : "qb", "year" : 2011 }
